[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Welcome to the Berlin Defense Simplified!"]
[Result "*"]

{ I can’t believe that this moment has finally arrived and my course on the Berlin is ready! Compiling this material has been a great challenge for me, but the greater the effort, the sweeter the reward.   Why the Berlin? There are a few factors that contributed to my choosing this theme. First, I would have to thank all my opponents who successfully played this rock-solid system against me over the years. It has been so frustrating trying to understand which piece to trade and which not to, and to still never be able to get it right! I often ended up avoiding the Ruy Lopez altogether, switching to the Italian or the Scotch game. There’s nothing wrong with these two, of course, but there was this sense that I was missing something.   Periodically, I would gather my courage and develop the bishop to b5, but my score against the Berlin never really improved, culminating with two painful losses last year @@StartBracket@@thank you, Teodora Injac and Anna Muzychuk!@@EndBracket@@. Avoiding the Berlin for almost my entire career, I became quite good at it, but I also gave it the powers to become a monster in my mind. I was afraid of it, I thought I couldn’t deal with it, and I didn’t think I had what it takes to understand it. I believe it also made me excessively respect those opponents who had this opening in their arsenal, which didn’t allow me to perform at my best.  Things started to change two years ago, with me reading the book ‘From London to Elista’, describing in great detail three of Kramnik’s World Championship matches, including the one which won him the title, against Kasparov. The book had instantly become one of my favourite, and I got this idea—how would it be for me to add the Berlin to my arsenal as well? It was just an idea and I viewed it more as a dream, one which I didn’t expect to materialize anytime soon. Most of my colleagues view me as a dynamic, or even aggressive player, which makes the Berlin not the first point of call when working on one’s repertoire. When I confessed to one friend about my new fascination with ‘The Wall’, they dismissed it in a joking manner—‘You and the Berlin?, Yeah, sure’. I think that it was that moment when I promised myself that I should get to the bottom of it. However, from said to done, there’s a long way to go.  Secondly, I’ve got to thank the wonderful Chessable team for believing in my abilities to ‘give birth’ to this course. There were moments when I thought I wouldn’t be able to finish it, but they kept being supportive and patient with me throughout sun and rain and wind as well. This gave me just enough time to find a way to deal with ‘the monster’. We have a healthy relationship these days—the phase of screaming and throwing things at each other is thankfully behind.   I don’t know if you can imagine my satisfaction when I successfully employed the Berlin with the Black pieces for the first time! It’s like some Mathematics or Physics concept that you couldn’t get around at school until it finally, all of a sudden, started to make sense. I got to test ‘the Wall’ in various contexts— in important games at the European Individual Women’s Championship, in the last round of an Open tournament, where the Berlin helped me get the overall 2nd place, and even in online blitz. The results were more than satisfying.   I can now say with confidence that Berlin and I understand each other and considering all the previous trauma, trust me—if I could do it, you will also be able to! I had the misconception that this opening is too complicated, with too many intricacies and nuances. Now, I believe that I can present it in a simple, logical, schematic manner. Intricacies and nuances are great and believe me, you will have the share of them as well, but not before learning the base. Take the chance to take this trip with me and avoid the 15 years of frustration I had to endure.   P.S. I may still be guilty of avoiding the Berlin when playing with the White pieces, but God, the satisfaction I get when seeing my opponents’ frowns when I employ it with Black… }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction to the Berlin Defense"]
[Result "*"]

1. --
{ The Berlin Endgame has a long history, being played as early as 1890 by Emanuel Lasker. However, most of us associate it with GM Vladimir Kramnik and his using it as a very effective weapon against then World Champion Garry Kasparov in their match for the world title in London, in 2000.  If the Berlin Endgame wasn’t a common guest at a high level until the match, things changed drastically after it. This is the effect of the great players - they inspire new directions! Even 24 years later, the Berlin Endgame is as rock solid as ever and continues to be one of Black’s main opening weapons.  In their match, Kramnik introduced the for those times unusual plan with Bd7, and Kc8- bringing his king to the queenside. He successfully made 2 draws with it, making one more using the ’old’ Ke8 plan. One could argue that the Berlin Endgame was the one to make Kramnik become World Champion, and it would be difficult to disagree.  In this course, I propose a different approach to the Berlin Endgame, which would be easier to navigate through. Here are some key points:  • Our main idea is to develop the dark-squared bishop to e7, aiming to trade one pair of knights by means of Nh4. It is generally advisable for Black to aim for a 2 bishops vs White’s bishop + knight position, as then we could try to exploit the advantage of the pair of bishops, but also have more squares to maneuver our pieces around.  • In most cases, our king will go to e8, from where it will protect the f7-pawn but also support attacking White’s pawn structure with f6. In the rare cases when our king will go to c8 it will mostly be because White’s dark-squared bishop will be on f4, x-raying our c7-pawn.  • The usual pawn construction we will go for on the queenside is a5, b6, c7, c6, and the c6 pawn might move to c5 if we have the d5-square covered or if White’s knights can’t jump to d5.  • Our strategy on the kingside is to provoke White into pushing their pawns, thus creating targets for us to attack. Our typical reaction to White’s expanding with g4 will be h5, in most of the cases, followed by capturing hxg4 and then continuing to attack White’s pawns with f6 or even f5.  I hope that these few points will help you have a better understanding of the lines that will follow! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Berlin Endgame, Main Line with 9.Rd1+ and 10.Nc3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ Developing a minor piece and attacking White's central pawn, what can be more natural? }
4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4
{ White has temporarily sacrificed a pawn to use their advantage in development to open up the e-file and start creating threats against our king. }
5... Nd6 6. Bxc6
{ The move which is played the most.  6.dxe5  ,  6.a4  ,  6.Ba4  and  6.Bg5  are the other possibilities, which we will explore in more detail in other chapters. }
6... dxc6 7. dxe5
{ 7.Nxe5  isn't challenging at all because we can simply finish our development with  7...Be7  , then  8.--  O-O  , where we'll enjoy a slight advantage thanks to our pair of bishops. }
7... Nf5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ This is the famous Berlin Endgame, the one that Kasparov failed to break. Since then, many other great GMs have had the same difficulties.  Back then @@StartBracket@@aprox 25 years ago@@EndBracket@@, it was believed that White had a clear advantage thanks to the superior pawn structure—4 pawns vs 3 on the kingside, while Black's majority isn't as great because of the doubled pawns. However, Kramnik and later almost every top GM concluded that Black's position is almost impossible to break. That is why recently the endgame has lost popularity and White more often tries other lines in their quest to find an advantage.  Let's have a look at the resulting positions and try to understand ourselves why this endgame is so poisonous. }
9. Rd1+
{ Has the advantage of forcing Black's king on e8 so it won't later have the option of going to the queenside by means of Bd7, Kc8. }
9... Ke8 10. Nc3 { The most natural developing move. } 10... Be7
{ The bishop develops while preparing the Nh4 idea. I like how it effectively works for us in most of the positions. White has many responses now,  11.h3  is the one that scores best.   By the way,  10...a5  is an interesting move that wasn't played often. The ones interested in widening their Berlin repertoire should look into it. }
11. h3
{ The move played most and the one which scores best for White. It doesn't have a clear-cut idea, and that's precisely the point: making a useful move while waiting for Black to show their plan. }
11... Nh4 { Staying true to our universal plan. } 12. Nxh4 Bxh4 13. Ne2
{ Once again- prophylaxis against Bf5. } 13... h5
{ We need to make it as difficult as possible for White to advance their pawns on the kingside. }
14. Be3 Be7 15. Rd2 h4
{ Fixing White's g2- and h3-pawns, while vacating the h5-square for a typical rook lift. }
16. Rad1 Rh5
{ Another way of applying pressure on the e5-pawn. The position is balanced. Our rook is happy on the 5th rank, and we can start working on the happiness of our other pieces - the light-squared bishop and the rook on a8. An effective way to do it is to prepare our usual rook trade on the d-file. }
