[Black "Berlin Endgame, Main Line with 9.Nc3 and 10.Bf4 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ Developing a minor piece and attacking White's central pawn, what can be more natural? }
4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4
{ White has temporarily sacrificed a pawn to use their advantage in development to open up the e-file and start creating threats against our king. }
5... Nd6 6. Bxc6
{ The move which is played the most.  6.dxe5  ,  6.a4  ,  6.Ba4  and  6.Bg5  are the other possibilities, which we will explore in more detail in other chapters. }
6... dxc6 7. dxe5
{ 7.Nxe5  isn't challenging at all because we can simply finish our development with  7...Be7  , then  8.--  O-O  , where we'll enjoy a slight advantage thanks to our pair of bishops. }
7... Nf5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ This is the famous Berlin Endgame, the one that Kasparov failed to break. Since then, many other great GMs have had the same difficulties.  Back then @@StartBracket@@aprox 25 years ago@@EndBracket@@, it was believed that White had a clear advantage thanks to the superior pawn structure—4 pawns vs 3 on the kingside, while Black's majority isn't as great because of the doubled pawns. However, Kramnik and later almost every top GM concluded that Black's position is almost impossible to break. That is why recently the endgame has lost popularity and White more often tries other lines in their quest to find an advantage.  Let's have a look at the resulting positions and try to understand ourselves why this endgame is so poisonous. }
9. Nc3 { The 'old' mainline. } 9... Be7
{ 9...Bd7  is the way for Blacks to aim for positions with their king on the queenside. It is also a perfectly healthy plan, though we choose to stick to our universal recipe here. }
10. Bf4
{ As in the other lines where White developed their bishop here, the main point is to eye the c7-pawn. Thus, we should beware of the potential e6 ideas. }
10... Be6 { The easiest way to stop e6 for good. } 11. Rad1+
{ Asking our king where does it want to go. } 11... Kc8
{ The other king move,  11...Ke8  , is also possible, but in this particular line, the king is better on c8, as it can later come to b7 after an eventual b7-b6 push, where we could even play for more than equality thanks to a good piece coordination. }
12. h3 a5 { The typical queenside space grab. } 13. Rfe1 c5
{ Taking away the d4-square from White's knight. } 14. Bg5
{ Now that our bishop can no longer go to b4, White manages forces the trade. }
14... h6 15. Bxe7 Nxe7
{ The position is balanced.   It is important to note that if our pawn were on c6 instead of c5, White would be better thanks to the Nd4 resource. Here, we have enough play linked with the control of the d4-square.   For White to make progress - they must prepare a pawn push on the kingside with f4, g4, f5. For that to happen - they must move their knight away from f3, which would leave the d4-square free for our knight to grab.  Meanwhile, we can bring our king to b7 and prepare a rook trade via the d-file. }
