1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3
{ This line is the most popular Anti-Berlin System, which Black faces most when playing the Berlin.   Tired of trying to prove any advantage in the Berlin Endgame, White protects the e4-pawn, keeping the queens on the board and aiming for a long, strategic battle.   Within, there are many mini-systems that White can try- but they mainly revolve around two main concepts - capturing on c6, or not.   • In the first, White will generally try to put pressure on the e5-pawn, as it can no longer be protected through d6.  • In the second, White will prepare d4, before or after castling short, maneuvering their knight from b1 to g3 or developing their dark-squared bishop. }
4... Bc5
{ The most popular and best scoring move for Black.   We develop the bishop to the most natural square while preparing to castle short.   White has several options. }
5. c3
{ The most useful and popular move. White will need this move in all lines because it's essential for playing d4. It also has the advantage of preventing Black's knight from reaching d4, unlike  5.O-O  . }
5... O-O
{ Castling makes the most sense, as we're still not certain where our d-pawn will land on d6 or d5. }
6. O-O
{ Again, it's both the most natural and the most popular move. White also brings their king to safety, waiting for us to decide how far we'd like to push the d-pawn. Both d5 and d6 are possible. }
6... d5
{ The most principled, aiming to open up the centre. White has two setups:  • One involving a pawn structure change after capturing on d5.  • And the other one - where they keep the tension in the centre.   • The most principled. White has two main directions - to capture on d5 or protect the pawn on e4 with Nbd2. }
7. Nbd2 dxe4 8. dxe4 a5
{ An important move aimed to keep White from taking space on the queenside by means of b4. }
9. Qc2
{ White's second most popular move, however, it scores best. The idea is to prepare the Nf1 knight reroute- vital for finishing the development of the queenside.   At the same time, the queen is placed best on c2, as compared to it being on e2, it not only protects the e4-pawn but also keeps the f1-a6 diagonal free for the bishop to retreat any time it might need to.   9.a4  Qe7  10.Qc2  Nb8  transposes. }
9... Qe7
{ Our setup remains unchanged- the d8-square is vacated for our rook. } 10. a4
Nb8
{ A typical knight retreat.   We want to be able to play c6, forcing White's bishop away from b5, while also taking the important d5-square under control, so that no light piece could land there.   Our knight will not stay on b8 for too long, as it can find better prospects on the kingside, where it will arrive taking the Nbd7-f8-g6 route. }
11. h3 { Prophilaxy against Bg4. } 11... Rd8 { We continue our plan. } 12. Re1
{ The most logical move and plan, preparing the Nf1 rerouting. } 12... Nbd7
{ It was also possible to start with  12...h6  instead. The position is balanced, as our knight will continue its trip towards g6. }
13. Bf1 b6
{ Our light-squared bishop will feel great on b7, from where it will attack the e4-pawn. }
14. Nb3 Bd6
{ We could give up the pair of bishops, but why make any compromises if we can easily avoid it? }
15. Be3 Bb7 { The e4-pawn is now hanging. } 16. Nbd2 h6
{ A useful, prophylactic move. Black is slightly better thanks to the better piece coordination. We can continue by trading the dark-squared bishops by means of  17.--  Bc5  , after which our knight from d7 is likely to land on c5, from where it will increase the pressure against the e4-pawn, while also eyeing the a4 one. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "4.d3 with 5.Bxc6 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3
{ This line is the most popular Anti-Berlin System, which Black faces most when playing the Berlin.   Tired of trying to prove any advantage in the Berlin Endgame, White protects the e4-pawn, keeping the queens on the board and aiming for a long, strategic battle.   Within, there are many mini-systems that White can try- but they mainly revolve around two main concepts - capturing on c6, or not.   • In the first, White will generally try to put pressure on the e5-pawn, as it can no longer be protected through d6.  • In the second, White will prepare d4, before or after short castling, maneuvering their knight from b1 to g3 or developing their dark-squared bishop. }
4... Bc5
{ The most popular and best scoring move for Black. We develop the bishop to the most natural square while preparing for a short castle. White has several options. }
5. Bxc6
{ White gives up the pair of bishops to double our pawns, hoping that they can make use of it, especially since we can no longer protect the e5-pawn with d6. The arising positions have a static character. }
5... dxc6
{ Don't get scared of the many options White has here. It is not vital to remember everything move by move, but to rather understand the ideas, this way - the correct move will come not from your memory, but from your understanding. First of all, the e5-pawn is untouchable. White will lose a piece after  6.Nxe5  Qd4  ,  with a double attack on f2 and e5. }
6. O-O
{ The most natural move and the second-most played. White's plan is quite straightforward, bring their knight from b1 to c4 and continue to increase the pressure against the e5-pawn. }
6... Bg4
{ A simple, but rather aggressive variation. We indirectly protect our e5-pawn by pinning White's knight. }
7. h3 { The most principled - making our bishop decide what to do. } 7... Bh5
{ Giving up the pair of bishops is premature; leaving only one good option. }
8. g4
{ The most principled. White wants to win the e5-pawn, shall our bishop retreat to g6. }
8... Nxg4 { A typical piece sacrifice, meant to open up White's kingside. } 9.
hxg4 Bxg4 10. Be3 { Being a piece up, trading any pieces will favour White. }
10... Be7 11. Kg2
{ The two best moves for White share the same idea: protect the knight on f3 to be able to unpin the queen.   11.Nbd2  , the second option White has to keep the balance, is analyzed here. While you can find the wrong  11.Kh1?  here. }
11... f5
{ 12.exf5  would be met by the short castle, where our rook will enjoy great prospects on the newly opened f file. }
12. Qe1 Bxf3+ 13. Kxf3 f4
{ It is quite easy to remember this concept of trapping White's bishop by means of f5-f4, following it up with a pawn storm on the kingside. }
14. Bd2 g5 15. Bc3 Qd6
{ With very good compensation for the sacrificed piece. We are ready to continue with long castle, g4 and h5. }
