[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "4.d3 with 5.O-O "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3
{ This line is the most popular Anti-Berlin System, which Black faces most when playing the Berlin.   Tired of trying to prove any advantage in the Berlin Endgame, White protects the e4-pawn, keeping the queens on the board and aiming for a long, strategic battle.   Within, there are many mini-systems that White can try- but they mainly revolve around two main concepts - capturing on c6, or not.   • In the first, White will generally try to put pressure on the e5-pawn, as it can no longer be protected through d6.  • In the second, White will prepare d4, before or after short castling, maneuvering their knight from b1 to g3 or developing their dark-squared bishop. }
4... Bc5
{ The most popular and best scoring move for Black. We develop the bishop to the most natural square while preparing for a short castle. White has several options. }
5. O-O
{ White brings their king to shelter, while protecting the f2-pawn, meaning that our e5-pawn is now hanging.   5...O-O  would be a mistake, as after  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.Nxe5  , White wins a pawn. }
5... Nd4
{ The best way to continue, as it solves all the potential problems:  • First, we no longer allow White to damage our pawn structure by capturing on c6.  • Secondly, we eliminate the attacker of the e5-pawn. }
6. Nxd4 Bxd4 7. c3
{ The most popular move. White makes the position resemble an Italian game, or Giuoco Piano, where their main idea is to play d4, getting control in the centre. }
7... Bb6
{ The best square for our bishop, as on c5 it would be exposed to b4 and d4 pushes. Although White has several ways to continue their development, none of them grant any advantage. }
8. Bg5
{ It's not a good idea to tempt us into playing h6, g5, as we will happily do so, taking advantage of our king not having castled yet. }
8... h6 9. Bh4
{ Freely giving up the pair of bishops didn't make sense, so White retreats. }
9... c6 10. Ba4 g5 11. Bg3 d6
{ Protecting the e5-pawn and planning on continuing the pawn storm on the kingside with h5-h4, where White's bishop will start missing the time when it was on c1. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "4.Bxc6 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. Bxc6
{ Looks somewhat unnatural, as compared to an Exchange Ruy Lopez, White takes on c6 without waiting for Black to play a6, so now we basically have an extra tempo, as instead of the not-so-useful a6 move we've developed our knight to f6.   There is another system we can compare it to as well.   If White reacts to our @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  with  4.d3  @@StartBracket@@see the 4. d3 line@@EndBracket@@,  then  4...Bc5  is the main continuation, where after  5.Bxc6  dxc6  , Black obtains a similar position to this one, but the bishop is a bit misplaced on c5. It will often have to go to d6 later to protect the e5-pawn.   Still, there are quite some games being played in this line, also by very strong players, so let's have a look! }
4... dxc6 { The best recapture, meant to open our light-squared bishop. } 5. d3
{ White guards their e4-pawn, planning to take our e5 one. } 5... Bd6
{ No need to give away free central pawns. } 6. O-O Qe7 7. Bg5
{ Compared to the  7.Nbd2  line, White wants to develop their bishop as well, as it had no other good prospects on c1. }
7... h6
{ The downside of White's last move is that it helps our plan of creating a kingside attack by means of a pawn expansion. We start by asking the bishop: where does it want to go next? }
8. Bxf6
{ 8.Bh4  isn't as great as after  8...g5  or first  8...Be6  followed by  9.--  g5  ,  White would have to retreat their bishop to g3, where it would be doing nothing other than being a potential target for our storming kingside pawns. }
8... Qxf6
{ White gave up both of their bishops but hoped that the closed and stable pawn structure would help their knights find some good squares. }
9. Nbd2 { Aiming for c4. } 9... Be6
{ The optimal place for our light-squared bishop as it keeps an eye on the c4-square and also doesn't stay in the way of our other pieces @@StartBracket@@compared let's say with when it would be on g4 instead and then we couldn't harmoniously push g5-g4@@EndBracket@@. }
10. Nc4 O-O-O
{ Ignoring the c4-knight for now. Trading it with  10...Bxc4  would also be possible, but would very likely lead to a drawish position, whereas here, we try to fight for an advantage. White's problem is that there's one good square for both of their knights - c4, meaning one of them would be unhappy. }
11. Qe2
{ 11.Nxd6  is also an option, though after  11...cxd6  , Black's pawn structure has improved and we'll make use of it by preparing d5 by means of  12.--  Rhe8  . }
11... Kb8 { Prophylaxis. } 12. a4
{ There are not too many plans White can come up with. The 2 most natural ones are either to take on d6 and try to consolidate following central strategy or take space on the queenside by means of pushing the a-pawn as far as possible. }
12... g5
{ While White tries to gain space on the queenside, we are doing exactly the same thing on the kingside,  13.--  g4  is a threat. }
13. a5 g4 { Forcing the f3-knight to a more passive position. } 14. Nfd2 Bc5
{ We no longer want to trade our dark-squared bishop for White's c4-knight, as it might be useful in our attack on the kingside. Black's position is preferable as our attack will be faster.  15.a6  can be met with  15...b6  , while our plan is to continue with the pawn storm with h6-h5, h5-h4, and g4-g3.   After  15.c3  or  15.Rfb1  , creating the threat of b2-b4, to push our bishop away, it should be met by  15...a6  , preparing the a7-square for our bishop to retreat to. }
