[Black "Four Knights Spanish, 5.O-O with 6.d3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. Nc3
{ White transposes to the Four Knights Opening - a very solid line, but one where they can't hope for any advantage.   White's knight on c3 protects the e4-pawn and is placed quite nicely - close to the centre, but, on the other hand, it takes away the c3-square from the pawn, giving up on the idea of controlling the centre with the pawns, which was otherwise possible after an eventual c3, followed by d4. }
4... Bb4
{ There were many ways to continue the development. This is the simplest, I think. At first, we copy the same thing that White does - putting pressure on the knight, which defends the central e4-pawn. }
5. O-O
{ The best White can try, finishing their development as fast as possible. }
5... O-O
{ A symmetrical position. We can't endlessly repeat White's move, as it would obviously lead to a disaster eventually. However, for now, there is nothing wrong with this strategy. }
6. d3
{ Protecting the e4-pawn and opening up the diagonal for the dark-squared bishop. }
6... Bxc3
{ There might be no other chance to double White's pawns on the c-file, as the knight from c3 was ready to go to e2. }
7. bxc3 d6 { Preparing to develop the last light piece, the bishop from c8. }
8. Bg5
{ White pins our f6-knight, hoping this would stop the Ne7-g6 maneuver. } 8...
Ne7
{ A simple plan. We are stubbornly going again for the knight rerouting, not being bothered by the possible doubling of the f-pawns. As previously mentioned, it is possible thanks to the f5-square being under our control, with the knight from e7 and the c8-bishop covering it. }
9. Bxf6
{ Let's examine what happens if White tries to use our doubled f-pawns to their advantage. }
9... gxf6 10. Nh4
{ Opens up the way for the queen to transfer to the kingside, while also trying to grip control over the f5-square and getting ready for playing f4. }
10... Ng6
{ 10...f5  was another fine way to continue. With our last move, we offer a knight trade, aiming to simplify the position. }
11. Nf5 { Fixing our doubled f-pawns, as they can no longer move now. } 11...
d5
{ We take advantage of White's e4-pawn not being able to move, as it has to protect the knight on f5. }
12. Ba4 { Prophylaxis against c6. } 12... a5
{ A typical move to gain space on the queenside while bothering White's bishop. }
13. Qh5 dxe4 14. dxe4 Bxf5 { The same way of simplifying the position. } 15.
Rfd1
{ White throws in an intermediate move, gaining temporary control over the d-file. }
15... Qe7
{ Our idea is to play against White's bishop, which is somewhat stuck on the queenside. }
16. exf5 Nf4 17. Qh6 Qc5
{ Threatening to trap the bishop with 18...b5, followed by 19...a4.   White has nothing better to do than take on f6 and give a perpetual by means of  18.Qxf6  ,  --  19.Qg5+  . }
