[Black "4.d4 with 5.O-O "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ With long variations to remember which still end with equality in the mainlines, the sidelines are becoming an often guest at both top level, and in our own mortals' games.This is the reason why I recommend paying by no means less attention when studying them. It is very likely that you'll encounter them more often than the mainlines. }
4. d4
{ The most direct way to try posing Black problems. White wants to open up the centre and create threats against our king. }
4... exd4 5. O-O
{ The most popular and best scoring move for White:  • They bring their king to safety, and introduces the idea of using the e-pawn to bother our knight on f6.  • They now also have the option of Rf1-Re1 up their sleeve. }
5... a6
{ Once again, we challenge White's bishop, making it go to a worse position, where it will get under tempi. It is very important to remember this idea, as otherwise, we might not be in time to finish our development under favourable circumstances.  The tarde  6.Bxc6  leads to a better position for us after  6...dxc6  thanks to the pair of bishops. }
6. Ba4
{ White hopes that by retreating the bishop to a4, they will not have to lose tempi due to potential attacks on the light-squared bishop. However, it is clear that the text move is more compromised than the bishop going to c4, as it is currently less active and does not enjoy the same prospects. }
6... Be7
{ We simply continue with our development, preparing to castle short. It would have given White more possibilities if we had done it on the previous move.   With their bishop on b5 rather than a4, they could use it on the f1-a6 diagonal - an option that they no longer have.   Chess is a game where limiting our opponent's possibilities is often more important than executing our own plans. }
7. e5
{ The most straightforward, taking space in the centre and forcing Black's knight to decide where it wants to land. }
7... Ne4
{ As usual, we want to be able to bring our knight to c5, from where it will bother White's bishop. }
8. Nxd4
{ The most natural- getting back the pawn and threatening to put pressure on the kingside by means of Nf5.   Black doesn't have time to go for the pair of bishops by means of  8...Nc5  given  9.Nf5  , sacrificing the bishop on a4, but aiming to get to our king after capturing on g7. }
8... O-O
{ The trade  9.Nxc6  dxc6  will lead to a favourable position for Black, as we'll either get the pair of bishops by means of  10.--  Nc5  , or trade the queens and head to a better endgame after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1pp1bppp/p1p5/4P3/B3n3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.c3  Qxd1  , where White will have trouble with the weak d3-square. }
9. Re1 { The best scoring move. } 9... Nxd4
{ We can throw in this intermediate move, as  10.Rxe4  doesn't really help White. We will answer it moving the knight,  10...Ne6  , where White won't be able to effectively stop the Nc5 threat. }
10. Qxd4 Nc5
{ Let's pretend that we're surprised we're getting the pair of bishops yet again. }
11. Nc3 d6
{ As White's light-squared bishop has no way to avoid being traded, we can start by opening our own bishop. }
12. Bb3 c6
{ Taking the d5-square away from White. We are somewhat better thanks to the incoming advantage of the bishops pair after we take on b3. }
