[Black "4.O-O with 6.Nxe5 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. Re1
{ The second most popular move after  5.d4  . White aims for a symmetrical position where they will try to use their advantage in development. }
5... Nd6
{ A retreat with tempo, attacking the bishop on b5. White will have several continuations to choose from. }
6. Nxe5
{ The mainline. The bishop on b5 is untouchable, given  6...Nxb5  7.Nxc6+  , where Black loses the queen. }
6... Be7
{ Covering the e-file and planning to castle short after White deals with the imminent threat of  7.--  Nxb5  . }
7. Bf1 Nxe5 8. Rxe5 O-O
{ Once again, our king is safe and we can focus on completing the development of our queenside. }
9. d4 Bf6
{ We need White's rook to go away as it covers the f5-square which we want to use for our knight. }
10. Re1 Nf5
{ This was our plan all along: to vacate the d-file for our pawn to move forward, opening up our light-squared bishop. }
11. c3 d5 { The light-squared bishop has become alive! } 12. Bf4
{ Another way of continuing the development. } 12... c6 13. Nd2
{ With White's knight aiming for the f3-square, we have two fine options here: the interesting 13... Nh4 as an alternative, and 13... Bg5. }
13... Bg5 { Our main continuation, to trade the dark-squared bishops first. }
14. Bxg5 Qxg5 15. Nf3 Qf6 16. Ne5 Nd6
{ White's knight is slightly more active than ours, this being the only reason why the engine gives a 0.09 advantage to White. }
17. Bd3 Bf5 18. Qf3 Rfe8
{ The position is equal, as White doesn't have a good way to make progress. We can continue bringing the 2nd rook to the centre with Rad8 and make small useful moves like a5 or Qg5 to prepare f6. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Avoiding the Endgame, 4.O-O with 5.d4 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4
{ Other than going for the Endgame line, White has a few other moves they can try, which cause no major troubles for us, though some precision is still needed to equalize comfortably. }
5... Nd6
{ Black has created the threat of taking on b5, thus White has a few options in dealing with it other than going for the Endgame Line after  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.dxe5  Nf5  . }
6. dxe5
{ The 2nd most popular continuation after  6.Bxc6  .   White temporarily sacrifices a piece.   6.Ba4  is the 3rd most popular move in the position and the most natural bishop retreat. Still, it involves a pawn sacrifice we will gladly accept. You'll find it here. }
6... Nxb5 7. a4
{ Our knight on b5 can't be saved, but we can choose on which square White will capture it. }
7... Nbd4
{ By placing our knight here, we avoid White's opening up the a-file for their rook after they would capture our knight on b5. }
8. Nxd4 d5
{ We are in time to immediately open the diagonal for our light-squared bishop. }
9. exd6
{ The mainline, White opens up the e-file, hoping to be able to create threats against our king. }
9... Nxd4 10. Qxd4 Qxd6
{ A queen trade would favour Black, as we have the pair of bishops and king safety won't be an issue anymore if entering an endgame. }
11. Qe4+ Qe6 { Another check- another queen's trade offer. } 12. Qd4 Qd6
{ The famous Berlin Draw by perpetual check. White may choose to keep on playing by delivering a check on e3. }
13. Qe3+
{ The idea is that now, after the typical  13...Qe6  , White has  14.Qg3  , targeting our c7- and g7-pawns, thus not allowing us time to comfortably finish our development. }
13... Be6
{ Taking advantage that White's queen isn't on e4, targeting our b7 pawn. } 14.
Nc3
{ White continues their development and threatens to jump with the knight to b5. At the same time, their queen keeps an eye on our a7-pawn, so that we can't castle long. }
14... a6
{ The best way to both stop the  15.Nb5  threat and solve the problem of the targeted a7-pawn. }
15. Rd1 Qc6
{ Our queen is comfortable on c6, as it targets the c2-pawn, so that White's knight would have difficulties to move away from c3. This line is analyzed in great detail in the last chapter of the course, starting here. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) The Berlin Endgame: Main Lines"]
[Black "9.h3 - 10.g4 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ Developing a minor piece and attacking White's central pawn, what can be more natural? }
4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4
{ White has temporarily sacrificed a pawn to use their advantage in development to open up the e-file and start creating threats against our king. }
5... Nd6 6. Bxc6
{ The move which is played the most.  6.dxe5  ,  6.a4  ,  6.Ba4  and  6.Bg5  are the other possibilities, which we will explore in more detail in other chapters. }
6... dxc6 7. dxe5
{ 7.Nxe5  isn't challenging at all because we can simply finish our development with  7...Be7  , then  8.--  O-O  , where we'll enjoy a slight advantage thanks to our pair of bishops. }
7... Nf5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ This is the famous Berlin Endgame, the one that Kasparov failed to break. Since then, many other great GMs have had the same difficulties.  Back then @@StartBracket@@aprox 25 years ago@@EndBracket@@, it was believed that White had a clear advantage thanks to the superior pawn structure, 4 pawns vs 3 on the kingside, while Black's majority isn't as great because of the doubled pawns. However, Kramnik and later almost every top GM concluded that Black's position is almost impossible to break. That is why recently the endgame has lost popularity and White more often tries other lines in their quest to find an advantage.  Let's have a look at the resulting positions and try to understand ourselves why this endgame is so poisonous. }
9. h3
{ The most fashionable try recently. White intends to force away our knight with g4 and insures that the g4-pawn will be protected.   The immediate  9.g4  would allow  9...Ne7  10.h3  h5  when White's pawns on the kingside become targets for Black. }
9... Be7
{ Our idea is simple: trade the knights on h4 and then play Bf5. White usually prevents this by playing g4. But then we can attack White's pawn construction on the kingside with h5. }
10. g4 { Chasing our knight away immediately. } 10... Nh4
{ But we are ready with out typical reaction- aiming to trade knights. } 11.
Nxh4
{ 11.Nd4  isn't good, as after  11...c5  , followed by  12.--  b6  , our light-squared bishop will be clearly a better piece than White's knight. }
11... Bxh4 12. Nc3
{ A natural way to continue the development.   12.Rd1+  Ke8  transposes to @@StartFEN@@r1bk3r/ppp1bppp/2p5/4Pn2/8/5N1P/PPP2PP1/RNB2RK1 w - - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Rd1+  Ke8  11.g4  Nh4  12.Nxh4  Bxh4  line.  @@StartFEN@@r1bk3r/ppp2ppp/2p5/4P3/6Pb/7P/PPP2P2/RNBR2K1 b - - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Ke7  would also be possible, but to avoid memorizing extra material, why not just transpose to a perfectly fine line? }
12... Ke7
{ If allowed, our king prefers to be on e7 rather than e8, as it doesn't interfere with our rooks' connection on the last rank and also supports f6-ideas better. }
13. Ne4 { A knight placed on a central square has the most possibilities! }
13... b6
{ Covering the c5-square and preparing to potentially develop our bishop to a6 or b7. }
14. Ng5
{ A tricky move with a dangerous threat, after  14...--  15.Nf3  our bishop on h4 will be trapped! }
14... Ke8 { Freeing the e7-square for our bishop. } 15. Nf3 Be7
{ Black's position is preferable thanks to the pair of bishops and White's weakened pawn structure on the kingside.  We'll follow up with  16...c5  and  17.--  Bb7  . White's knight on f3 isn't better placed than it was on c3, as it gets in the way of the f2-pawn, thus a potential h5 breakthrough would be hard to parry. }
