{ The move which is played the most.  6.dxe5  ,  6.a4  ,  6.Ba4  and  6.Bg5  are the other possibilities, which we will explore in more detail in other chapters. }
6... dxc6 7. dxe5
{ 7.Nxe5  isn't challenging at all because we can simply finish our development with  7...Be7  , then  8.--  O-O  , where we'll enjoy a slight advantage thanks to our pair of bishops. }
7... Nf5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ This is the famous Berlin Endgame, the one that Kasparov failed to break. Since then, many other great GMs have had the same difficulties.  Back then @@StartBracket@@aprox 25 years ago@@EndBracket@@, it was believed that White had a clear advantage thanks to the superior pawn structure—4 pawns vs 3 on the kingside, while Black's majority isn't as great because of the doubled pawns. However, Kramnik and later almost every top GM concluded that Black's position is almost impossible to break. That is why recently the endgame has lost popularity and White more often tries other lines in their quest to find an advantage.  Let's have a look at the resulting positions and try to understand ourselves why this endgame is so poisonous. }
9. Rd1+
{ Has the advantage of forcing Black's king on e8 so it won't later have the option of going to the queenside by means of Bd7, Kc8. }
9... Ke8 10. Nc3 { The most natural developing move. } 10... Be7
{ The bishop develops while preparing the  Nh4  idea. I like how it effectively works for us in most of the positions. White has many responses now,  11.h3  is the one that scores best.   By the way,  10...a5  is an interesting move that wasn't played often. The ones interested in widening their Berlin repertoire should look into it. }
11. Bg5
{ Stops our Nh4 idea, but allows another simplification, which we know that favours the side that has less space. }
11... Bxg5 12. Nxg5 h6
{ It might look like the knight on g5 doesn't do much, but it actually gets in our bishop's way to develop to its most desired square, e6. }
13. Nf3 Be6 { White is not in time to stop trading a pair of rooks. } 14. Rd2
Rd8 15. Rad1 Rxd2 16. Rxd2
{ White has managed to stop us from bringing the other rook to the centre.  16...Ke7  would be a big blunder, as after  17.g4  , our knight would be trapped. }
16... a5
{ A useful move which we will see often in this endgame. It not only takes space on the queenside, but also prepares the a4 move in case White's knight will move away from c3. The point is that we'll be able to capture the a2-pawn without worrying about our bishop getting trapped there after an eventual b3, as we will have the a4 resource. }
17. a3 { Prophylaxis, White doesn't want to risk losing the a2-pawn. } 17...
Bd7
{ If White can use prophylaxis, so can we! With the a2-pawn no longer being a target, Black doesn't need the bishop on e6.   We want to reroute our knight to g6 via e7, which will leave the d4-square free for White's knight. That's what our last move prepared for, the bishop has already avoided the trade on e6 after White's eventual Nd4. It is not necessarily the absolutely best move, but facing moves which prevent their ideas might become quite frustrating for your opponents, which could lead to mistakes. }
18. h4 { White stops any potential g5 ideas . } 18... Ne7
{ The position is balanced. We can choose from two good plans.   • One is to bring our knight to g6 and then build up some pressure on the e5-pawn by means of Ke7, Re8, and Kf8.   • The 2nd plan is to limit White's light pieces even more with c5 and b6, after which we can transfer our king to c8, and the bishop to c6, while the rook can still come to e8 to bother White's e5-pawn. }
