{ We are now prepared to open up the position for our bishops. } 15. e6
{ White correctly tries to keep matters 'closed'. } 15... Bc8 16. Ng3
{ The idea is to be able to protect the e6-pawn by playing Re1. } 16... a6
{ We prepare the c5 push, after which we might be able to win the e6-pawn. }
17. Ndf5 Nxf5 18. Nxf5
{ White is ready to capture on g7, should we take the e6-pawn. } 18... g6
{ White's pawn isn't going anywhere, but ours can! } 19. Rxd8+ Kxd8 20. Rd1+
{ A somewhat forced sequence follows. } 20... Ke8 21. Nxe7 Kxe7 22. Ba3+ Kxe6
23. Re1+ Kd7 { We need the king to protect the c7-pawn. } 24. Re7+ Kd8
{ We are a pawn up, but White's activity compensates for that, making the position balanced. We can follow up with Re8 or first, Bf5. }
