[White "1) The Berlin Endgame: Main Lines"]
[Black "9.Rd1+ - 10.Nc3 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ Developing a minor piece and attacking White's central pawn, what can be more natural? }
4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4
{ White has temporarily sacrificed a pawn to use their advantage in development to open up the e-file and start creating threats against our king. }
5... Nd6 6. Bxc6
{ The move which is played the most.  6.dxe5  ,  6.a4  ,  6.Ba4  and  6.Bg5  are the other possibilities, which we will explore in more detail in other chapters. }
6... dxc6 7. dxe5
{ 7.Nxe5  isn't challenging at all because we can simply finish our development with  7...Be7  , then  8.--  O-O  , where we'll enjoy a slight advantage thanks to our pair of bishops. }
7... Nf5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ This is the famous Berlin Endgame, the one that Kasparov failed to break. Since then, many other great GMs have had the same difficulties.  Back then @@StartBracket@@aprox 25 years ago@@EndBracket@@, it was believed that White had a clear advantage thanks to the superior pawn structure—4 pawns vs 3 on the kingside, while Black's majority isn't as great because of the doubled pawns. However, Kramnik and later almost every top GM concluded that Black's position is almost impossible to break. That is why recently the endgame has lost popularity and White more often tries other lines in their quest to find an advantage.  Let's have a look at the resulting positions and try to understand ourselves why this endgame is so poisonous. }
9. Rd1+
{ Has the advantage of forcing Black's king on e8 so it won't later have the option of going to the queenside by means of Bd7, Kc8. }
9... Ke8 10. Nc3 { The most natural developing move. } 10... Be7
{ The bishop develops while preparing the  Nh4  idea. I like how it effectively works for us in most of the positions. White has many responses now,  11.h3  is the one that scores best.   By the way,  10...a5  is an interesting move that wasn't played often. The ones interested in widening their Berlin repertoire should look into it. }
11. Bf4
{ It looks like the best square for the bishop, as it not only protects the e5-pawn, but also makes e6 ideas possible, as our pawn on c7 will be hanging. }
11... Nh4 { Our universal recipe, trade the knights. } 12. Nd4
{ Let's see how we follow-up if White tries to avoid the knight trade. } 12...
Nf5
{ We stalk White's poor knight, forcing it to make a choice: either trade it or place it in an inferior position. }
13. Nde2
{ Is White's knight happy here? An easy way to find out is to count the squares where the knight can jump to and compare it to those which it had on e4 or f3. It is clear that by default, on e2 the knight has 2 squares less than it would on either f3 or e4, making its placement inferior. }
13... Be6 { Part 2 of our universal recipe: prepare the rook trade. } 14. Ne4
Rd8 15. f3
{ Consolidating the knight and preparing the f2-square for the king. } 15...
Nh4
{ With the e7-square being taken by our bishop, we find a different way to reroute our knight to  g6. }
16. Bg3 Ng6 17. Nd4
{ White hopes to get rid of our light-squared bishop, as it has no opponent on the board, making their job of covering the light squares a difficult task.   The advance  17.f4  is premature, as it weakens the light squares too much.  17...Bf5  Targeting the e4-knight, which can't leave, as the c2-pawn will fall.  18.N2c3  Bb4  All of White's pieces are stuck: the bishop has to protect the f4-pawn, and the knights can't move as well. We have a significant advantage as White doesn't have a good way to stop our  19.--  Bxc3  20.Nxc3  Bxc2  threat. }
17... Bd5
{ We're ready to trade this bishop, but on our terms! Doubling White's pawns on the e-file would be convenient. The position is balanced. If White plays the most logical  18.Re1  , we can answer with  18...h5  and 19...h4- forcing White's light pieces to worse squares, while building up pressure against the e5-pawn. }
