{ A perfectly good square for our bishop, keeping an eye on the c2-pawn and preparing the long castle. }
11. g4
{ An interesting try- White not only attacks our bishop, but also takes away from our queen the h4-square, so now  11...--  12.Rd1  , followed by  12...--  13.Be3  is an unpleasant threat. }
11... Qe4
{ A nice tactical trick, forcing White to trade queens, as they will otherwise have a big problem with the pawn on c2. For example,  12.Be3  runs into  12...Qxc2  , while  12.Qxe4  Bxe4  leaves us with a superior position as well, thanks to the week c2-pawn and White's weakened kingside pawn structure. }
12. Re1
{ Trying to win a tempi, so that after trading the queens, White's rook would be on e2, protecting the c2-pawn. }
12... Qxe2 13. Rxe2
{ It appears that now the c2-pawn is protected so our bishop must go away from f5, but... }
13... O-O-O
{ Another nice trick. We continue our development, ignoring White's threat and making one of our own instead!  14.gxf5  runs into  14...Rd1  and we'll take our piece back on c1, leaving White with a very sad position. }
14. Nc3 { Now the f5-bishop will finally have to move. } 14... Be6 15. Bg5 Rd7
{ The position is balanced. We will soon finish our development through Bc5 and then we might challenge White's bishop by playing h6 and then choose between Bc4, h5, and g5 or Rhd8 depending of where White bishop will retreat. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) The Berlin Endgame: Other Tries"]
[Black "8.Qe2 Nd4 9.Nxd4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ Developing a light piece and attacking White's central pawn, what can be more natural? }
4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4
{ White has temporarily sacrificed a pawn, but try to use their advantage in development to open up the e-file and start creating threats against our king. }
5... Nd6 6. Bxc6
{ The move which is played the most  6.dxe5  ,  6.a4  ,  6.Ba4  and  6.Bg5  are the other possibilities which we delve into in a different chapter. }
6... dxc6 7. dxe5
{ 7.Nxe5  isn't challenging at all because we can simply finish our development with  7...Be7  , then  8.--  O-O  , where we'll enjoy a slight advantage thanks to our pair of bishops. }
7... Nf5 8. Qe2
{ White avoids going into the endgame and tries to prove that their pawn majority advantage on the kingside weighs heavier than our pair of bishops with the queens on board. }
8... Nd4
{ Trading White's best piece and vacating the f5-square for our bishop. } 9.
Nxd4 Qxd4
{ Threatening the very unpleasant  10.--  Bg4  , as the f-pawn is pinned and won't be able to move.   For example,  10.Nc3  runs into  10...Bg4  , and White's queen has no good squares to move to. Black's advantage is significant. }
10. h3 { Prophylaxis against our  10...Bg4  . } 10... Bf5
{ A perfectly good square for our bishop, keeping an eye on the c2-pawn and preparing the long castle. }
11. Nc3 { Covers the e4-square while continuing to develop. } 11... O-O-O 12.
g4
{ An interesting move, asking us a question, where to retreat on, e6 or g6? The answer isn't easy. To choose correctly, we must understand that it's important for us to have the c8-square available for our bishop. }
12... Be6
{ Actually, even without doing all the necessary calculations, it could be possible to deduct this move to be the best, as here the bishop is most functional and that's what one must seek when choosing where to place their pieces. Compared to being on g6, our bishop controls more squares @@StartBracket@@longer diagonals@@EndBracket@@ and can play both an attacking as well as a defensive role. }
13. Rd1 Qb6
{ Following a line close to the @@StartFEN@@2kr1b1r/ppp2ppp/2p5/4Pb2/3q2P1/2N4P/PPP1QP2/R1B2RK1 b - g3 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Bg6  variation. }
14. Rxd8+ Kxd8 15. Bg5+
{ Have you already guessed the move that will save our day at the end of the critical line? The one we looked at after @@StartFEN@@2kr1b1r/ppp2ppp/2p5/4Pb2/3q2P1/2N4P/PPP1QP2/R1B2RK1 b - g3 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Bg6?  ...You can pause for a moment and try to figure it out! }
15... Kc8 16. Rd1 Bc5 { So far the moves are exactly the same. } 17. Qd2
{ Will actually lead to an inferior position for White now.  17.Ne4  is better, but after  17...h6  some exchanges will follow leading to an equal position. }
17... Kb8
{ Eureka! Now it is clear why the bishop had to go to e6 to be able to cover our king from checks. With no attack whatsoever White can count on. Black is better thanks to the pair of bishops and White's weakened pawn structure and king. }
