[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) The Berlin Endgame: Other Tries"]
[Black "8.Qxd8+ Kxd8 9.b3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ Developing a light piece and attacking White's central pawn, what can be more natural? }
4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4
{ White has temporarily sacrificed a pawn, but try to use their advantage in development to open up the e-file and start creating threats against our king. }
5... Nd6 6. Bxc6
{ The move which is played the most  6.dxe5  ,  6.a4  ,  6.Ba4  and  6.Bg5  are the other possibilities which we delve into in a different chapter. }
6... dxc6 7. dxe5
{ 7.Nxe5  isn't challenging at all because we can simply finish our development with  7...Be7  , then  8.--  O-O  , where we'll enjoy a slight advantage thanks to our pair of bishops. }
7... Nf5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ This is the famous Berlin Endgame, which Kasparov couldn't break and many other top GMs followed in his footsteps. Back then, @@StartBracket@@aprox 25 years ago@@EndBracket@@ it was believed that White had a clear advantage thanks to the superior pawn structure- 4 pawns vs 3 on the kingside, while Black's majority isn't as great because of the doubled pawns.  However, Kramnik and later almost every top GM concluded that Black's position is almost impossible to break. That is why in recent years the endgame has lost popularity and White more often tries other lines in their quest to find an advantage.   Let's have a look at the resulting positions and try to understand ourselves why this endgame is so posionous. }
9. b3
{ Aiming to fianchetto the bishop was a popular plan in the past. These days, it is believed to be harmless for Black, as we get enough time to seek cover for our king on the queenside. }
9... Be7 { Keeping the Nh4 ideas in mind. } 10. Bb2 Bd7
{ Our king is ready now to walk to c8 and eventually, to b7. } 11. Nc3 a5
{ The usual pawn push directed against a fianchetto construction. } 12. Ne4 h5
{ Securing the position of our knight on f5. } 13. Nfg5
{ White tries to exploit the position of our king; the f7-pawn has become vulnerable with our king being on d8 rather than on e8. }
13... Rf8 14. Rad1 Kc8
{ The position is balanced, though I would already prefer Black here, as their play is easier.   While things are stable on the kingside, the queenside might start giving White headaches.  15...a4  is an unpleasant threat. If that does not prove to be enough, we can follow up with c5, Bc6, b5 - continuing to create threats on the queenside. }
*

