9. O-O a6 10. Ba4 Nh5
{ We don’t want to capture the bad bishop on g3. The purpose of our last move is different: we are preparing the f5 push, aiming for g6, and eventually Ng7. }
11. Nxe5 { Doesn't work. } 11... Nxe5
{ 12.Qxh5  loses the queen after  12...Bg4  . } 12. Bxe5 dxe5 13. Qxh5 Qxd3
{ Getting the pawn back and tempting White to take on e5.   After  14.Re1  , the queen's move  14...Qd6  would also lead to an advantage for us, thanks to the pair of bishops. }
14. Qxe5 Bd6
{ A nice resource! White can't hold on to their e4-pawn, as after  15.Qd4  they would lose an exchange after  15...Bxh2  16.Kxh2  Qxf1  . }
15. Qh5 Qxe4
{ Black has a significant advantage thanks to the pair of bishops, good piece coordination, and open nature of the position.  White's queen is really misplaced,  16.--  Bg4  is a rather unpleasant threat, along with the obvious @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/1pp2pp1/p2b3p/7Q/B3q3/2P5/PP3PPP/RN3RK1 w - - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16.--  Qxa4  . }
