[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3
{ This line is the most popular Anti-Berlin System, which Black faces most when playing the Berlin.   Tired of trying to prove any advantage in the Berlin Endgame, White protects the e4-pawn, keeping the queens on the board and aiming for a long, strategic battle.   Within, there are many mini-systems that White can try- but they mainly revolve around two main concepts - capturing on c6, or not.   • In the first, White will generally try to put pressure on the e5-pawn, as it can no longer be protected through d6.  • In the second, White will prepare d4, before or after castling short, maneuvering their knight from b1 to g3 or developing their dark-squared bishop. }
4... Bc5
{ The most popular and best scoring move for Black.   We develop the bishop to the most natural square while preparing to castle short.   White has several options. }
5. c3
{ The most useful and popular move. White will need this move in all lines because it's essential for playing d4. It also has the advantage of preventing Black's knight from reaching d4, unlike  5.O-O  . }
5... O-O
{ Castling makes the most sense, as we're still not certain where our d-pawn will land on d6 or d5. }
6. O-O
{ Again, it's both the most natural and the most popular move. White also brings their king to safety, waiting for us to decide how far we'd like to push the d-pawn. Both d5 and d6 are possible. }
6... d5
{ The most principled, aiming to open up the centre. White has two setups:  • One involving a pawn structure change after capturing on d5.  • And the other one - where they keep the tension in the centre. The most principled. White has two main directions - to capture on d5 or protect the pawn on e4 with Nbd2. }
7. exd5
{ As a rule, the one who takes off the tension in the centre first usually makes a compromise, which is rarely a good thing. There's nothing wrong with it in this case, but Black will not face too many problems either. }
7... Qxd5 8. Bc4 Qd8
{ The best square for our queen.  8...Qd6  might have looked tempting, but after  9.b4  Bb6  10.Ba3  , the  10...--  11.b5  threat would make our queen regret not choosing another square in the first place. }
9. Nbd2 { The move which was played most. } 9... a5
{ An ambitious move, leading to some complications. The main idea is to stop White from playing b4. }
10. h3 a4
{ A novelty. Its idea is to limit White's pieces as much as possible- the b3-square is no longer available for White. This move was never tried before, however, Nils Grandelius has taken notice of it as well in his Grand Ruy Lopez course, where he recommends  11.Re1  . }
11. Re1
{ Nils' recommendation makes a lot of sense- White increases the pressure against the e5-pawn and prosaically wants to take it. }
11... Qd6
{ The best way to protect the pawn, as we're not prepared to play  11...Re8  in view of  12.Ng5  , where our f7-pawn would have to answer some unpleasant questions. }
12. Qe2 { Let's see how to react if White continues to put pressure on e5. }
12... Bf5
{ By choosing this move order, we avoid the materially imbalanced position we get after  12...h6  13.Nxe5  . It is a safer option if you don't feel like going for a wild game. }
13. Ng5
{ Let's see what happens if White tries to take advantage of our not having played h6 yet.   The line  13.Bb5  h6  transposes to @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/1pp2ppp/2nq1n2/2b1p3/p1B5/2PP1N1P/PP1NQPP1/R1B1R1K1 b - - 3 12@@EndFEN@@  12...h6  13.Bb5  Bf5  . }
13... Bb6
{ With White having the possibility to jump to e4, we go away from the fork. }
14. Nde4 Nxe4 15. Nxe4
{ Imagine Black's bishop still on c5, we'd be forced to trade one of our bishops for White's knight. Even though that wouldn't be a tragedy, why allow White even the slightest psychological edge? }
15... Qg6
{ The position is balanced as we have threats, one tactical and the other strategical. The first is to capture on h3, while the 2nd is to play  16.--  Be6  to trade the bishops. We will be able to bring our rooks to the centre and put pressure on White's d3-pawn. }
*

