{ A novelty. Its idea is to limit White's pieces as much as possible- the b3-square is no longer available for White. This move was never tried before, however, Nils Grandelius has taken notice of it as well in his Grand Ruy Lopez course, where he recommends  11.Re1  . }
11. Re1
{ Nils' recommendation makes a lot of sense- White increases the pressure against the e5-pawn and prosaically wants to take it. }
11... Qd6
{ The best way to protect the pawn, as we're not prepared to play  11...Re8  in view of  12.Ng5  , where our f7-pawn would have to answer some unpleasant questions. }
12. Qe2 { Let's see how to react if White continues to put pressure on e5. }
12... h6
{ Is an interesting option which leads to some complications. The idea is simple, take the g5-square under control in order to be able to play Re8 without worrying about the f7-pawn. }
13. Bb5 { White intends to capture on c3 and then on e5. } 13... Bf5
{ The best defence is attack! We put pressure on White's d3-pawn, so that after  14.Bxc6  , we'd have the intermediate  14...Bxd3  . }
14. Ne4
{ Solves the issue regarding the pressure on d3, but gives up their pressure against the e5-pawn. }
14... Nxe4 15. dxe4 Be6
{ The position is balanced, as the pressure against the e5- and d3-pawns are eliminated. We'll continue by bringing our f-rook to d8, while if  16.Bxc6  we can always capture with the pawn, where we'll get the pair of bishops as compensation for the doubled pawns. }
