1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3
{ This line is the most popular Anti-Berlin System, which Black faces most when playing the Berlin.   Tired of trying to prove any advantage in the Berlin Endgame, White protects the e4-pawn, keeping the queens on the board and aiming for a long, strategic battle.   Within, there are many mini-systems that White can try- but they mainly revolve around two main concepts - capturing on c6, or not.   • In the first, White will generally try to put pressure on the e5-pawn, as it can no longer be protected through d6.  • In the second, White will prepare d4, before or after castling short, maneuvering their knight from b1 to g3 or developing their dark-squared bishop. }
4... Bc5
{ The most popular and best scoring move for Black.   We develop the bishop to the most natural square while preparing to castle short.   White has several options. }
5. c3
{ The most useful and popular move. White will need this move in all lines because it's essential for playing d4. It also has the advantage of preventing Black's knight from reaching d4, unlike  5.O-O  . }
5... O-O
{ Castling makes the most sense, as we're still not certain where our d-pawn will land on d6 or d5. }
6. O-O
{ Again, it's both the most natural and the most popular move. White also brings their king to safety, waiting for us to decide how far we'd like to push the d-pawn. Both d5 and d6 are possible. }
6... d5
{ The most principled, aiming to open up the centre. White has two setups:  • One involving a pawn structure change after capturing on d5.  • And the other one - where they keep the tension in the centre. The most principled. White has two main directions - to capture on d5 or protect the pawn on e4 with Nbd2. }
7. Nbd2 dxe4 8. dxe4 a5
{ An important move aimed to keep White from taking space on the queenside by means of b4. }
9. Qe2
{ The most popular move, though one which doesn't score too well for White. }
9... Qe7 { Protecting our e5-pawn. } 10. a4 Na7
{ Fighting against White's most active piece, no longer allowing White to spoil our pawn structure by capturing on c6. }
11. Bd3 Nc6
{ With no one bothering our knight, it can safely return closer to the centre. }
12. Nc4
{ White tries to finish their development. The bishop from c1 will likely move next, for White to connect their rooks. }
12... Rd8 { Once again, the best place for a rook is on an open file! } 13. Be3
h6
{ Creating a 'luft' for our king, while also taking the g5-square under control, so that we won't have to worry of any Bg5 or Ng5 jumps. }
14. Rad1 Be6
{ We finish our development while getting the extra option to simplify the position by means of Bxc4. }
15. h3 { 15...Nh5  The ambitious option, aiming for the f4-square. } 15... Bxc4
{ Simple and good. } 16. Bxc4 Rxd1 17. Rxd1 Bxe3 18. Qxe3 Rd8
{ We offer one trade after another, drying up the position. } 19. Rxd8+ Qxd8
20. Bb5 { Creating the threat of taking on c6 and then on e5. } 20... Qd6
{ We want to capture c6 with the queen- with a double attack on the e4- and a4-pawns. The position is equal. }
