7. Nbd2 dxe4 8. dxe4 a5
{ An important move aimed to keep White from taking space on the queenside by means of b4. }
9. Qc2
{ White's second most popular move, however, it scores best. The idea is to prepare the Nf1 knight reroute- vital for finishing the development of the queenside.   At the same time, the queen is placed best on c2, as compared to it being on e2, it not only protects the e4-pawn but also keeps the f1-a6 diagonal free for the bishop to retreat any time it might need to.   9.a4  Qe7  10.Qc2  Nb8  transposes. }
9... Qe7
{ Our setup remains unchanged- the d8-square is vacated for our rook. } 10. a4
Nb8
{ A typical knight retreat.   We want to be able to play c6, forcing White's bishop away from b5, while also taking the important d5-square under control, so that no light piece could land there.   Our knight will not stay on b8 for too long, as it can find better prospects on the kingside, where it will arrive taking the Nbd7-f8-g6 route. }
11. h3 { Prophilaxy against Bg4. } 11... Rd8 { We continue our plan. } 12. Nb3
{ Engine's top choice, though no humans went for it. } 12... Bb6
{ We don't need to make compromises- parting with our bishop isn't necessary. }
13. Re1 Ne8
{ Our knights maneuver as they please- the 2nd knight heads to d6. } 14. Nbd2
{ White argues that their knight has done its job- pushing our bishop back and tries rerouting it. }
14... Nd6
{ The knight is placed very well on d6, as it controls many important squares- c4, b5, and e4. At the same time, by vacating the f6-square, we get the option of protecting our e5-pawn by means of f6, thus freeing our queen to do more important things. }
15. Nc4
{ White basically forces a knight trade, as we can't allow them to take on b6, which would shatter our pawn structure on the queenside. }
15... Nxc4 16. Bxc4
{ With our f7-pawn pinned,  16...--  17.Bg5  becomes a serious threat. } 16...
h6 { The only available way of taking the g5-square under control. } 17. Be3
Bxe3 18. Rxe3 Nd7 19. Rd3 { White wants to double on the only open file. }
19... Re8
{ We are not in time to directly fight for the d-file, as our e5-pawn will be hanging in many variations. However, we have an indirect way of fighting for the only open file. We want to bring our knight to b6 and then the bishop will come to c6 via d7, from where it will bother White's e4- and a4-pawns. This plan allows us to keep the position balanced. }
