{ For some mysterious reason, this move scores best. However, there are no objective reasons for that, as they will have to play h3 anyway if they want to bring their knight on f1 without getting in trouble after either Ng4 or Bg4. }
11... h6
{ It is interesting to notice how we can start with any of our typical moves. Both  11...Rd8  and  11...Nbd7  where possible and likely to transpose into @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/1pp1qppp/2n2n2/pBb1p3/4P3/2P2N2/PPQN1PPP/R1B2RK1 w - - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10.h3  . }
12. Nf1
{ Let's see how we can exploit White's trying to do without the h3 prophylactic move. }
12... Bd7
{ Immediately offering to trade White's most active piece- their light-squared bishop. }
13. Bc4 Ng4
{ Without the h3-pawn covering the g4-square, why not bother the f2-pawn? } 14.
Re2
{ The only way to avoid massive simplification while protecting the f2-pawn, unlike  14.Ne3  or  14.Be3  . }
14... Be6
{ White's bishop has a choice- either retreat to the passive d3 or agree for the trade. }
15. Qb3
{ 15.Bd3  would be met by  15...Qd6  , where  16.--  Rd8  would be an unpleasant threat- bothering the bishop on d3 greatly. }
15... Bxc4 16. Qxc4 Nd7
{ The best square for the b8-knight, from where it can continue its way to greener pastures, such as the g6-square for example. }
17. h3 Ngf6 18. Ng3
{ White has managed to get control over the f5-square by having eliminated our light-squared bishop. However, one should ask themselves- is it dangerous? }
18... Rfe8 { The answer is 'No'. } 19. Nf5 Qe6
{ Offering a queen trade, as with them off the board, White can't count on using their active f5-knight in order to create an attack on the kingside. }
20. Qd3 Qc6
{ The best square for our queen, as it puts pressure on the e4- and a4-pawns. Black is somewhat better thanks to the superior piece coordination. We can continue preparing Nc5 through Bf8, which will make the pressure felt by the e4-pawn unbearable. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) 4.d3: Other Tries"]
[Black "4.d3 Bc5 5.Bxc6 with 6.O-O #1 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3
{ This line is the most popular Anti-Berlin System, which Black faces most when playing the Berlin.   Tired of trying to prove any advantage in the Berlin Endgame, White protects the e4-pawn, keeping the queens on the board and aiming for a long, strategic battle.   Within, there are many mini-systems that White can try- but they mainly revolve around two main concepts - capturing on c6, or not.   • In the first, White will generally try to put pressure on the e5-pawn, as it can no longer be protected through d6.  • In the second, White will prepare d4, before or after short castling, maneuvering their knight from b1 to g3 or developing their dark-squared bishop. }
4... Bc5
{ The most popular and best scoring move for Black. We develop the bishop to the most natural square while preparing for a short castle. White has several options. }
5. Bxc6
{ White gives up the pair of bishops to double our pawns, hoping that they can make use of it, especially since we can no longer protect the e5-pawn with d6. The arising positions have a static character. }
5... dxc6
{ Don't get scared of the many options White has here. It is not vital to remember everything move by move, but to rather understand the ideas, this way - the correct move will come not from your memory, but from your understanding. First of all, the e5-pawn is untouchable. White will lose a piece after  6.Nxe5  Qd4  ,  with a double attack on f2 and e5. }
6. O-O
{ The most natural move and the second-most played. White's plan is quite straightforward, bring their knight from b1 to c4 and continue to increase the pressure against the e5-pawn. }
6... Bg4
{ A simple, but rather aggressive variation. We indirectly protect our e5-pawn by pinning White's knight. }
7. Be3
{ The bishop trade doesn't favour anyone - both on e3 and on c5 - the resulting positions are balanced. }
7... Nd7
{ The knight didn't have great prospects on f6. Hence, it's moving to d7, vacating the f6-square for a potential pawn move, should we need to protect the e5-pawn one more time. }
8. Nbd2 { White simply continues their development. } 8... Bxe3
{ We could have also done this on the previous move, but with White's knight still being on b1, they would have some additional options like Qe1-Qa5, which they no longer have here. }
9. fxe3 Qe7
{ The position is equal, but I would take Black any day here. Let me explain the reasons. Black's plan is clear here:  • Play f6.  • Bring the bishop to e6, so that a potential White's knight on c4 would have to worry if we want to trade it.  • Take space on the queenside through a5, b6.  • Do not hurry with castling, as depending on White's next moves, we could choose to long castle, aiming for an attack on the kingside.   The problem White will face is the lack of a clear plan. Pushing the pawns in the centre is not a good idea as they will become targets and what else to do? }
*

