[White "4) 4.d3: Other Tries"]
[Black "4.d3 Bc5 5.Bxc6 with 6.O-O #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3
{ This line is the most popular Anti-Berlin System, which Black faces most when playing the Berlin.   Tired of trying to prove any advantage in the Berlin Endgame, White protects the e4-pawn, keeping the queens on the board and aiming for a long, strategic battle.   Within, there are many mini-systems that White can try- but they mainly revolve around two main concepts - capturing on c6, or not.   • In the first, White will generally try to put pressure on the e5-pawn, as it can no longer be protected through d6.  • In the second, White will prepare d4, before or after short castling, maneuvering their knight from b1 to g3 or developing their dark-squared bishop. }
4... Bc5
{ The most popular and best scoring move for Black. We develop the bishop to the most natural square while preparing for a short castle. White has several options. }
5. Bxc6
{ White gives up the pair of bishops to double our pawns, hoping that they can make use of it, especially since we can no longer protect the e5-pawn with d6. The arising positions have a static character. }
5... dxc6
{ Don't get scared of the many options White has here. It is not vital to remember everything move by move, but to rather understand the ideas, this way - the correct move will come not from your memory, but from your understanding. First of all, the e5-pawn is untouchable. White will lose a piece after  6.Nxe5  Qd4  ,  with a double attack on f2 and e5. }
6. O-O
{ The most natural move and the second-most played. White's plan is quite straightforward, bring their knight from b1 to c4 and continue to increase the pressure against the e5-pawn. }
6... Bg4
{ A simple, but rather aggressive variation. We indirectly protect our e5-pawn by pinning White's knight. }
7. Bg5
{ GM Gajewski's recommendation, answering our pin with one of their own. The move hasn't been tried yet on a high level. }
7... h6 8. Bh4 Qe7 { Preparing to castle long. } 9. Nbd2 O-O-O
{ With our king safe, we can now start some action on the Kingside. } 10. Bg3
{ It targets the e5-pawn. } 10... Nh5
{ One of the best options for us. It involves a pawn sacrifice to keep the initiative. The main point is that our knight is much more active on h5 than on d7, and it will be able to create important threats against White's king.   White has to take on e5 if wanting to try for anything; otherwise, we'll defend the e5-pawn by means of f6 and then play g5 and focus on attacking the kingside.   10...Nd7?!  Is the only move analysed by GM Gajewski, where White can get a nice edge thanks to the fact that they'd be able to play c3, as their pawn on d3 is no longer hanging with our knight covering the d file. However, there are better options we can choose from.  11.h3  Bh5  12.c3  White's chances are better here thanks to their idea of rolling the pawns on the queenside, whilst Black's attack on the kingside isn't coming with a similar speed. }
11. Bxe5 f6 12. Bg3 { This is already a serious mistake. } 12... Nxg3 13. hxg3
h5
{ Threatening to play  14.--  h4  and open up the h file against White's poor king. Black's attack is very dangerous. }
