{ A simple, but rather aggressive variation. We indirectly protect our e5-pawn by pinning White's knight. }
7. h3 { The most principled - making our bishop decide what to do. } 7... Bh5
{ Giving up the pair of bishops is premature; leaving only one good option. }
8. g4
{ The most principled. White wants to win the e5-pawn, shall our bishop retreat to g6. }
8... Nxg4 { A typical piece sacrifice, meant to open up White's kingside. } 9.
hxg4 Bxg4 10. Be3 { Being a piece up, trading any pieces will favour White. }
10... Be7 11. Kh1
{ Was played by Hikaru Nakamura in a rapid game versus Magnus Carlsen. It is a serious mistake, leading to a lost position for White. }
11... f5
{ Black aims for the f4 lock, followed by a pawn storm on the kingside. } 12.
Rg1 h5 13. Nc3 f4 14. Bd2 g5
{ With a winning position, as White has no play at all, while Black can bring their queen to d6 and then castle long, after which the pawns on the kingside will continue rolling. Surprisingly, Magnus managed to lose this position. }
