{ A simple, but rather aggressive variation. We indirectly protect our e5-pawn by pinning White's knight. }
7. h3 { The most principled - making our bishop decide what to do. } 7... Bh5
{ Giving up the pair of bishops is premature; leaving only one good option. }
8. g4
{ The most principled. White wants to win the e5-pawn, shall our bishop retreat to g6. }
8... Nxg4 { A typical piece sacrifice, meant to open up White's kingside. } 9.
hxg4 Bxg4 10. Be3 { Being a piece up, trading any pieces will favour White. }
10... Be7 11. Kg2
{ The two best moves for White share the same idea: protect the knight on f3 to be able to unpin the queen. }
11... f5
{ 12.exf5  would be met by the short castle, where our rook will enjoy great prospects on the newly opened f file. }
12. Qe1 Bxf3+ 13. Kxf3 f4
{ It is quite easy to remember this concept of trapping White's bishop by means of f5-f4, following it up with a pawn storm on the kingside. }
14. Bd2 g5 15. Bc3 Qd6
{ With very good compensation for the sacrificed piece. We are ready to continue with long castle, g4 and h5. }
