{ This move has quite a good score, though it still doesn't have too many followers because objectively, the knight isn't placed so well on c3, as it has limited squares it can jump to, none of them creating any serious threats. }
6... Qe7 { Protecting the e5 pawn. } 7. Be3
{ Let's examine this move, as it allows a somewhat unusual maneuver which can be useful to remember. }
7... Bxe3 8. fxe3 Ng4
{ The knight heads to d6 via h6-f7. It would be faster to get there via e8, but our king occupies that square, and we're not rushing to free it, as we'd like to castle long. At the same time, White has to deal with the e3-pawn being attacked. }
9. Qe2 Bd7 { Preparing to castle long. } 10. O-O-O f6
{ The position is somewhat better for Black thanks to the easier play. The knight will head to d6, after which we can grab space on the queenside with a5, b6, bring our king to b7, and then maybe even start a pawn storm on the kingside with h5, g5, gaining even more space, thus cramping White's pieces. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) 4.d3: Other Tries"]
[Black "4.d3 Bc5 5.Bxc6 with 6.Nc3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3
{ This line is the most popular Anti-Berlin System, which Black faces most when playing the Berlin.   Tired of trying to prove any advantage in the Berlin Endgame, White protects the e4-pawn, keeping the queens on the board and aiming for a long, strategic battle.   Within, there are many mini-systems that White can try- but they mainly revolve around two main concepts - capturing on c6, or not.   • In the first, White will generally try to put pressure on the e5-pawn, as it can no longer be protected through d6.  • In the second, White will prepare d4, before or after short castling, maneuvering their knight from b1 to g3 or developing their dark-squared bishop. }
4... Bc5
{ The most popular and best scoring move for Black. We develop the bishop to the most natural square while preparing for a short castle. White has several options. }
5. Bxc6
{ White gives up the pair of bishops to double our pawns, hoping that they can make use of it, especially since we can no longer protect the e5-pawn with d6. The arising positions have a static character. }
5... dxc6
{ Don't get scared of the many options White has here. It is not vital to remember everything move by move, but to rather understand the ideas, this way - the correct move will come not from your memory, but from your understanding. First of all, the e5-pawn is untouchable. White will lose a piece after  6.Nxe5  Qd4  ,  with a double attack on f2 and e5. }
6. Nc3
{ This move has quite a good score, though it still doesn't have too many followers because objectively, the knight isn't placed so well on c3, as it has limited squares it can jump to, none of them creating any serious threats. }
6... Qe7 { Protecting the e5 pawn. } 7. h3
{ Once again, White stops us from developing our bishop to g4, but it also has some downsides, the main one being that White will have to think twice before castling short, as we'll have the h3 'hook' to exploit in our attack on the kingside. }
7... h6 { Preparing g5 in case White will castle short. } 8. Be3 Bd6
{ Taking on e3 was also possible, but let's investigate the type of position where we try to keep as many pieces as possible on the board - a more ambitious approach. }
9. Qe2 Be6 { We let the bishop out before bringing our knight to d7. } 10. a3
Nd7
{ With a similar plan to the ones we've seen before - castle long and prepare the f5-break. }
11. d4 { White can try to open-up the centre first. } 11... f5
{ We are ready to answer with a counterblow, as our light pieces nicely support the pawns. The position is balanced. }
