{ White has created a hook for us to attack:  b3, which we immediately do! } 9.
Bb2 Nd7 10. Ng5
{ The best way of trading our light-squared bishop, as compared to  10.Nc4  , it doesn't spoil White's pawn structure. }
10... a4
{ Well, we'll no longer castle long, but White will have to guess - do we want to take on b3, or maybe we'd like to push the a pawn to a3? }
11. Ndf3 f6 12. Nxe6 Qxe6
{ Look how nicely we've worked to neutralize White's fianchettoed bishop by building the g7, f6, e5 pawn chain! }
13. Nh4
{ White can try to make use of the f5-square for their knight, while preparing to attack our pawn chain with f4. }
13... O-O 14. Nf5 g6 { No need to put up with White's knight. } 15. Ng3 Bd6
{ This not only vacates the c5-square for our knight, but also fights against f4. }
16. Ne2 { White stubbornly prepares the f-pawn push. } 16... Qe7
{ Wouldn't it be nice to bring our knight to e6? } 17. Qd2 Nc5 18. f4
{ Just in time, as we would otherwise play Ne6, making f4 very difficult to achieve. }
18... exf4 19. Nxf4 Be5
{ We are also in time to trade White's bishop, which has gained good prospects now that our e5-pawn is gone. White can't avoid this by playing  20.d4  , as we have the intermediate  20...Nxe4  , which wins a pawn.   Should White choose to capture on e5, we'll surely recapture with the pawn, gaining control over the d4-square.   Once the bishops are off the board, only Black can be better, thanks to the potential play on the a-file and somewhat weak White's dark squares. }
