1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3
{ This line is the most popular Anti-Berlin System, which Black faces most when playing the Berlin.   Tired of trying to prove any advantage in the Berlin Endgame, White protects the e4-pawn, keeping the queens on the board and aiming for a long, strategic battle.   Within, there are many mini-systems that White can try- but they mainly revolve around two main concepts - capturing on c6, or not.   • In the first, White will generally try to put pressure on the e5-pawn, as it can no longer be protected through d6.  • In the second, White will prepare d4, before or after short castling, maneuvering their knight from b1 to g3 or developing their dark-squared bishop. }
4... Bc5
{ The most popular and best scoring move for Black. We develop the bishop to the most natural square while preparing for a short castle. White has several options. }
5. Bxc6
{ White gives up the pair of bishops to double our pawns, hoping that they can make use of it, especially since we can no longer protect the e5-pawn with d6. The arising positions have a static character. }
5... dxc6
{ Don't get scared of the many options White has here. It is not vital to remember everything move by move, but to rather understand the ideas, this way - the correct move will come not from your memory, but from your understanding. First of all, the e5-pawn is untouchable. White will lose a piece after  6.Nxe5  Qd4  ,  with a double attack on f2 and e5. }
6. Nbd2
{ The best square for the knight. At the same time, White doesn't hurry with castling, waiting to see our setup first. It is the best scoring move for White and the most popular one. }
6... Be6 { Stopping White from jumping to c4. } 7. O-O
{ White castles without having created any weaknesses, or 'hooks' on the kingside, while reinforcing the threat of taking on e5. }
7... Qd6
{ The simplest. We will need our bishop on b6 to cover the a5-square.   8.Ng5  is premature, as it will run into  8...Bg4  , forcing the knight to return. }
8. b3 { Aiming to fianchetto the bishop. } 8... a5
{ White has created a hook for us to attack:  b3, which we immediately do! } 9.
Bb2 Nd7 10. Ng5
{ The best way of trading our light-squared bishop, as compared to  10.Nc4  , it doesn't spoil White's pawn structure. }
10... a4
{ Well, we'll no longer castle long, but White will have to guess - do we want to take on b3, or maybe we'd like to push the a pawn to a3? }
11. Ndf3 f6 12. Nxe6 Qxe6
{ Look how nicely we've worked to neutralize White's fianchettoed bishop by building the g7, f6, e5 pawn chain! }
13. d4 { White can attack our pawn chain using their d-pawn. } 13... exd4 14.
Nxd4 Bxd4 15. Qxd4
{ White has partly managed to open a path for their bishop and hopes to create a passed pawn in the centre with f4, e5. }
15... Kd8
{ A very cool move! With White having a pawn majority on the kingside, as well as their bishop looking in that direction and the incoming f4, e5 pawn storm, our king will feel safer on the queenside. As the long castle wasn't an option because of the a4-pawn, we chose to walk with our king instead. }
16. Rfe1 Kc8
{ The position is balanced, as we'll continue playing b6, followed by Kb7. The h rook will come to e8, after which we can even double our rooks on the e-file, putting pressure on White's e4-pawn. }
*

