1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3
{ This line is the most popular Anti-Berlin System, which Black faces most when playing the Berlin.   Tired of trying to prove any advantage in the Berlin Endgame, White protects the e4-pawn, keeping the queens on the board and aiming for a long, strategic battle.   Within, there are many mini-systems that White can try- but they mainly revolve around two main concepts - capturing on c6, or not.   • In the first, White will generally try to put pressure on the e5-pawn, as it can no longer be protected through d6.  • In the second, White will prepare d4, before or after short castling, maneuvering their knight from b1 to g3 or developing their dark-squared bishop. }
4... Bc5
{ The most popular and best scoring move for Black. We develop the bishop to the most natural square while preparing for a short castle. White has several options. }
5. O-O
{ White brings their king to shelter, while protecting the f2-pawn, meaning that our e5-pawn is now hanging.   5...O-O  would be a mistake, as after  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.Nxe5  , White wins a pawn. }
5... Nd4
{ The best way to continue, as it solves all the potential problems:  • First, we no longer allow White to damage our pawn structure by capturing on c6.  • Secondly, we eliminate the attacker of the e5-pawn. }
6. Nxd4 Bxd4 7. Nd2
{ The 2nd most popular move, but the one which scores best. White intends to bring their knight quickly to f3, asking our pawn on e5 and the dark-squared bishop some serious questions. }
7... c6
{ A useful move, as it not only attacks White's bishop, but will also support the d5-pawn push. }
8. Ba4 O-O
{ We are very close to finishing the development, only the light-squared bishop needs to come into play. }
9. Nf3
{ White stays true to their plan, bothering both our bishop on d4 and the e5-pawn. }
9... Bb6
{ We sacrifice a pawn to avoid White getting the pair of bishops by taking on d4, while they would also get a favourable pawn structure, with a pawn majority on the kingside which will start rolling rapidly. }
10. Nxe5 d5
{ We will get nice piece activity as compensation for the sacrificed pawn. }
11. exd5 Qxd5 12. Nf3 Bg4
{ Creating an unpleasant pin. Look at our pieces - they are placed very well, making up for our missing pawn. }
13. h3 Bh5
{ White can't afford to play  14.g4  , as after  14...Nxg4  15.hxg4  Bxg4  ,  the pin will be deadly and White's king too exposed. We'll simply bring a rook on the kingside with Rfe8-Re6-Rg6 and win the game. }
14. Bb3 Qd6 { Taking away the d4-square from White's bishop. } 15. a4 a5
{ We enjoy good compensation for the sacrificed pawn thanks to the deadly pin of the f3-knight and our piece activity. White struggles to improve the position of their pieces, while we can simply bring our rooks to the central files and then consider rerouting our knight to f4 via d5. }
