1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3
{ This line is the most popular Anti-Berlin System, which Black faces most when playing the Berlin.   Tired of trying to prove any advantage in the Berlin Endgame, White protects the e4-pawn, keeping the queens on the board and aiming for a long, strategic battle.   Within, there are many mini-systems that White can try- but they mainly revolve around two main concepts - capturing on c6, or not.   • In the first, White will generally try to put pressure on the e5-pawn, as it can no longer be protected through d6.  • In the second, White will prepare d4, before or after short castling, maneuvering their knight from b1 to g3 or developing their dark-squared bishop. }
4... Bc5
{ The most popular and best scoring move for Black. We develop the bishop to the most natural square while preparing for a short castle. White has several options. }
5. O-O
{ White brings their king to shelter, while protecting the f2-pawn, meaning that our e5-pawn is now hanging.   5...O-O  would be a mistake, as after  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.Nxe5  , White wins a pawn. }
5... Nd4
{ The best way to continue, as it solves all the potential problems:  • First, we no longer allow White to damage our pawn structure by capturing on c6.  • Secondly, we eliminate the attacker of the e5-pawn. }
6. Nxd4 Bxd4 7. c3
{ The most popular move. White makes the position resemble an Italian game, or Giuoco Piano, where their main idea is to play d4, getting control in the centre. }
7... Bb6
{ The best square for our bishop, as on c5 it would be exposed to b4 and d4 pushes. Although White has several ways to continue their development, none of them grant any advantage. }
8. Na3
{ Unlike after the other knight move  8.Nd2  ,  White clearly says that their knight will stay on the queenside, most likely landing on c4, from where it will attack the e5-pawn and hope to get the pair of bishops by capturing on b6. }
8... c6
{ We create a potential place for our bishop to retreat - the c7-square. } 9.
Ba4 d6
{ We never hurry with castling, as White still doesn't want to open up the centre with d4, as their e4-pawn is unprotected.   10.Nc4  would be met by  10...Bc7  ,  which would create the 11... b5 threat. }
10. Bb3
{ Both bishop retreats are possible. White basically prepares themselves for playing 11. Nc4, where after 11...Bc7, 12...b5 wouldn't be a deadly threat. White's light-squared bishop has the best prospects on the a2-g8 diagonal indeed. However, Black has a very effective way to bother it, demonstrated by Levon Aronian in a game versus Magnus Carlsen in 2015, at the European Team Championship. }
10... a5
{ Taking space on the kingside, while also getting ready to bother White's bishop with a4. }
11. Nc4 Ba7
{ 11...Bc7  was equally good, it's just a matter of taste.   We want to push our pawns on the queenside now - both  12.--  b5  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/bp3ppp/2pp1n2/p3p3/2N1P3/1BPP4/PP3PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 2 12@@EndFEN@@  12.--  a4  being serious threats. }
12. a4 { The only way for White to stop our pawns from rolling. } 12... O-O
{ White doesn't have any other good way of finishing their development other than the text move, as  13.Be3  runs into  13...b5!  , where Black will actually be better. }
13. Bg5 h6 14. Bxf6
{ White gets tempted by the possibility of winning a pawn, wrongly assessing the outcome.  14.Bh4  was better, though not enough for more than equality after  14...g5  15.Bg3  Bg4  , followed by  16.--  Nh5  . }
14... Qxf6 15. Nxa5 d5 16. exd5
{ Taking the 2nd pawn would lead to White losing a piece. } 16... cxd5 17. Bxd5
Qd8
{ With a double attack on d5 and a5. The only way to try saving both pieces is to take on b7 with the bishop. }
18. Bxb7 Bxb7 19. Nxb7 Qc7
{ White's knight is trapped for good. White will have some compensation for the piece, as they have 3 pawns for it, but that's only enough for a slight hope to save the game. }
