[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) 4.d3: Other Tries"]
[Black "4.d3 Bc5 5.O-O #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3
{ This line is the most popular Anti-Berlin System, which Black faces most when playing the Berlin.   Tired of trying to prove any advantage in the Berlin Endgame, White protects the e4-pawn, keeping the queens on the board and aiming for a long, strategic battle.   Within, there are many mini-systems that White can try- but they mainly revolve around two main concepts - capturing on c6, or not.   • In the first, White will generally try to put pressure on the e5-pawn, as it can no longer be protected through d6.  • In the second, White will prepare d4, before or after short castling, maneuvering their knight from b1 to g3 or developing their dark-squared bishop. }
4... Bc5
{ The most popular and best scoring move for Black. We develop the bishop to the most natural square while preparing for a short castle. White has several options. }
5. O-O
{ White brings their king to shelter, while protecting the f2-pawn, meaning that our e5-pawn is now hanging.   5...O-O  would be a mistake, as after  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.Nxe5  , White wins a pawn. }
5... Nd4
{ The best way to continue, as it solves all the potential problems:  • First, we no longer allow White to damage our pawn structure by capturing on c6.  • Secondly, we eliminate the attacker of the e5-pawn. }
6. Nxd4 Bxd4 7. c3
{ The most popular move. White makes the position resemble an Italian game, or Giuoco Piano, where their main idea is to play d4, getting control in the centre. }
7... Bb6
{ The best square for our bishop, as on c5 it would be exposed to b4 and d4 pushes. Although White has several ways to continue their development, none of them grant any advantage. }
8. d4
{ Isn't of great effect, as the e4-pawn will be hanging, though not immediately, as after  8...Nxe4  9.Re1  , Black would be in serious trouble. }
8... O-O 9. dxe5 Nxe4 10. Bd3 d5
{ We are actually better here, thanks to the advantage in development and better piece coordination. We can follow up with Qe7, Be6, or even the f6-break. }
*

