1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. Bxc6
{ Looks somewhat unnatural, as compared to an Exchange Ruy Lopez, White takes on c6 without waiting for Black to play a6, so now we basically have an extra tempo, as instead of the not-so-useful a6 move we've developed our knight to f6.   There is another system we can compare it to as well.   If White reacts to our @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  with  4.d3  @@StartBracket@@see the 4. d3 line@@EndBracket@@,  then  4...Bc5  is the main continuation, where after  5.Bxc6  dxc6  , Black obtains a similar position to this one, but the bishop is a bit misplaced on c5. It will often have to go to d6 later to protect the e5-pawn.   Still, there are quite some games being played in this line, also by very strong players, so let's have a look! }
4... dxc6 { The best recapture, meant to open our light-squared bishop. } 5.
Nxe5 { Gives Black an easy advantage. } 5... Qd4 { Double attack! } 6. Nf3
Qxe4+ 7. Qe2
{ 7.Kf1  is a sad move to play. Black could respond with  7...Bg4  , followed by  8.--  O-O-O  , with a significant advantage thanks to the pair of bishops and White's unsafe king. }
7... Qxe2+ 8. Kxe2 Bd7
{ Black has a pleasant, long-term advantage due to their pair of bishops and safer king after  9.--  O-O-O  . }
