[White "5) 4.Bxc6"]
[Black "4.Bxc6 dxc6 5.d3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. Bxc6
{ Looks somewhat unnatural, as compared to an Exchange Ruy Lopez, White takes on c6 without waiting for Black to play a6, so now we basically have an extra tempo, as instead of the not-so-useful a6 move we've developed our knight to f6.   There is another system we can compare it to as well.   If White reacts to our @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  with  4.d3  @@StartBracket@@see the 4. d3 line@@EndBracket@@,  then  4...Bc5  is the main continuation, where after  5.Bxc6  dxc6  , Black obtains a similar position to this one, but the bishop is a bit misplaced on c5. It will often have to go to d6 later to protect the e5-pawn.   Still, there are quite some games being played in this line, also by very strong players, so let's have a look! }
4... dxc6 { The best recapture, meant to open our light-squared bishop. } 5. d3
{ White guards their e4-pawn, planning to take our e5 one. } 5... Bd6
{ No need to give away free central pawns. } 6. h3
{ Taking the g4-square under control, thus preventing our bishop from landing there. }
6... h6 { We can do exactly the same! } 7. Nbd2 Be6
{ Whenever White's knight is ready to jump to c4, we want to have the possibility of capturing it with our bishop. }
8. b3
{ A useful move- preparing both developing the bishop to b2, from where it wants to put some pressure on the e5-pawn and also making sure that the c4-square is controlled by the b-pawn too, to be able to recapture over there without losing the e4-pawn. }
8... Qe7
{ The best place for the queen- we need the d7 one vacant for our knight so that it can protect the e5-pawn. At the same time, we now can castle long. }
9. Bb2 Nd7
{ Our e5-pawn is protected. Next, we'll need to finish our development by castling short or long. }
10. Nc4
{ 10.O-O  doesn't change much, as we'll still respond with  10...O-O-O  , followed by  11.--  g5  with an attack on the kingside. }
10... Bxc4
{ Now White will have a choice- what to recapture with? It's nice that our response will be similar in both cases. }
11. bxc4 O-O-O
{ White could argue that compared to the position where they capture with the d-pawn, they have the b-file open here as a bonus. True, but not too dangerous for us, as even if White manages to double the queen and a rook on the b-file, creating the threat of mate on b7, we'll be able to easily defend by playing b6. }
12. O-O g5 { Our attack is much faster - h5 and g4 are coming. } 13. a4 a5
{ Now, this move is more of a psychological one, meant to discourage White from having even the slightest hope of an attack.   We didn't really need it, as even if White would manage to play a5 on the next move, they would still need to move the bishop away from b2, then double on the b-file - that's about 5 moves to just create a threat which we could meet with b6, protecting everything.   However, even now that isn't possible, while our attack is not easy to stop at all h5 and g4 is coming. Thus, Black has a significant advantage. }
