[Black "4.Bxc6 dxc6 5.d3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. Bxc6
{ Looks somewhat unnatural, as compared to an Exchange Ruy Lopez, White takes on c6 without waiting for Black to play a6, so now we basically have an extra tempo, as instead of the not-so-useful a6 move we've developed our knight to f6.   There is another system we can compare it to as well.   If White reacts to our @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  with  4.d3  @@StartBracket@@see the 4. d3 line@@EndBracket@@,  then  4...Bc5  is the main continuation, where after  5.Bxc6  dxc6  , Black obtains a similar position to this one, but the bishop is a bit misplaced on c5. It will often have to go to d6 later to protect the e5-pawn.   Still, there are quite some games being played in this line, also by very strong players, so let's have a look! }
4... dxc6 { The best recapture, meant to open our light-squared bishop. } 5. d3
{ White guards their e4-pawn, planning to take our e5 one. } 5... Bd6
{ No need to give away free central pawns. } 6. O-O Qe7 7. Nbd2
{ White aims to jump to c4, the optimal square for the knight, as it attacks both the e5-pawn and the bishop on d6. }
7... Be6
{ Kramnik said in one of his courses that chess is basically a game of reaction and prophylaxis, where one of the most important questions one has to ask oneself before making every move is 'What does my opponent want to do?'. Well, here we use this question to easily find the best move to stop White's  8.Nc4  , which would be a blunder after  8...Bxc4  9.dxc4  Nxe4  , with a pawn up for Black. }
8. a4
{ Trying to take some space on the queenside and hoping to provoke some weaknesses in our camp. }
8... O-O-O
{ Why not? Our king will be safe on the queenside, the centre is stable, so we will be able to start an attack on the kingside preparing g5. }
9. a5 a6
{ Creating a nice blockade and making it very hard for White to create threats towards our king on the queenside. }
10. b3 { Aiming for the c4-knight jump. } 10... Kb8
{ A typical prophylactical move. The king is almost always safer on b8 when castling long, as it guards the a7-square @@StartBracket@@or pawn in some cases@@EndBracket@@ and also it vacates the c8-square, in case we'll need to bring in a piece @@StartBracket@@most probably the light-squared bishop@@EndBracket@@ to the defence of our queenside. }
11. Nc4 Bb4
{ With better prospects for Black thanks to the safe position of the king, pair of bishops, White's weakness of the dark squares @@StartBracket@@b4, c3, d4, a5@@EndBracket@@ and the prospects of an attack on the kingside. We can continue with  12.--  Nd7  ,  13.--  f6  , protecting our e5-pawn, then choose from launching a pawn storm through g5, h5, h4, and g4 or maneuvering our knight to f4 via Nf8-g6. }
