[Black "5.O-O #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. Nc3
{ White transposes to the Four Knights Opening - a very solid line, but one where they can't hope for any advantage.   White's knight on c3 protects the e4-pawn and is placed quite nicely - close to the centre, but, on the other hand, it takes away the c3-square from the pawn, giving up on the idea of controlling the centre with the pawns, which was otherwise possible after an eventual c3, followed by d4. }
4... Bb4
{ There were many ways to continue the development. This is the simplest, I think. At first, we copy the same thing that White does - putting pressure on the knight, which defends the central e4-pawn. }
5. O-O
{ The best White can try, finishing their development as fast as possible. }
5... O-O
{ A symmetrical position. We can't endlessly repeat White's move, as it would obviously lead to a disaster eventually. However, for now, there is nothing wrong with this strategy. }
6. Bxc6
{ White changes the pawn structure, hoping to be able to put pressure on our e5-pawn and prove that the knights are more effective than the bishops. }
6... dxc6
{ 7.Nxe5  will be met by  7...Bxc3  8.dxc3  and  8...Nxe4  with an equal position. }
7. d3 { Protecting the e4-pawn and threatening to take now on e5. } 7... Nd7
{ The best way to protect the e5-pawn. Our knight wasn't doing much on f6 any longer. Now we are preparing to reroute it by means of Re8 and Nf8. }
8. Ne2
{ White aims to bring their knight to g3 from where it will eye the f5-square. }
8... Re8 { Simply continuing our plan of rerouting the knight via f8. } 9. Ng3
Nf8
{ With a balanced position. We'll continue by bringing our dark-squared bishop to d6, as it doesn't do anything on b4, and then we could take space on the queenside through a5 and b6. On the kingside, we can bring our knight to g6, while the queen can jump to f6- preparing the Nf4 jump. }
