1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. Nc3
{ White transposes to the Four Knights Opening - a very solid line, but one where they can't hope for any advantage.   White's knight on c3 protects the e4-pawn and is placed quite nicely - close to the centre, but, on the other hand, it takes away the c3-square from the pawn, giving up on the idea of controlling the centre with the pawns, which was otherwise possible after an eventual c3, followed by d4. }
4... Bb4
{ There were many ways to continue the development. This is the simplest, I think. At first, we copy the same thing that White does - putting pressure on the knight, which defends the central e4-pawn. }
5. O-O
{ The best White can try, finishing their development as fast as possible. }
5... O-O
{ A symmetrical position. We can't endlessly repeat White's move, as it would obviously lead to a disaster eventually. However, for now, there is nothing wrong with this strategy. }
6. d3
{ Protecting the e4-pawn and opening up the diagonal for the dark-squared bishop. }
6... Bxc3
{ There might be no other chance to double White's pawns on the c-file, as the knight from c3 was ready to go to e2. }
7. bxc3 d6 { Preparing to develop the last light piece, the bishop from c8. }
8. h3
{ White takes the g4-square under control, in order to stop a potential Bg4. }
8... Ne7
{ As White hasn't traded our knight, it heads to better pastures, which in this case is the g6-square, from where it will support the e5-pawn without being bothered, unlike from c6. }
9. Bg5
{ White creates the threat of taking on f6, which would force us to capture back with the pawn. It might look as something we'd like to avoid, as it opens up our king and somewhat compromises our pawn structure.   However, in this case, it's actually nothing too dangerous, as White can't use the g-file to their advantage and, very importantly- can't take the f5-square under control, as both our knight from e7 and c8-bishop cover it, making a potential f5 move only a question of good timing. }
9... Ng6 { Our knight continues it's trip. } 10. Nh4
{ White is ready to increase the pressure on the f6-knight. With our 2nd knight being already on g6, a potential  10...--  11.Qf3  followed by  11...--  12.Bxf6  becomes more dangerous, as White will now have control over the f5-square, making our doubled f-pawns a serious weakness. }
10... h6
{ The easiest solution to solve all the issues regarding the pinned f6-knight. Black is somewhat better thanks to the superior pawn structure and piece harmony.   11.Nxg6  would only help us, as we'll be able to use the newly opened f-file to put pressure on White's king. Otherwise, we can prepare a break in the centre by means of Be6 and c6, followed by an eventual d5. }
