1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. Nc3
{ White transposes to the Four Knights Opening - a very solid line, but one where they can't hope for any advantage.   White's knight on c3 protects the e4-pawn and is placed quite nicely - close to the centre, but, on the other hand, it takes away the c3-square from the pawn, giving up on the idea of controlling the centre with the pawns, which was otherwise possible after an eventual c3, followed by d4. }
4... Bb4
{ There were many ways to continue the development. This is the simplest, I think. At first, we copy the same thing that White does - putting pressure on the knight, which defends the central e4-pawn. }
5. O-O
{ The best White can try, finishing their development as fast as possible. }
5... O-O
{ A symmetrical position. We can't endlessly repeat White's move, as it would obviously lead to a disaster eventually. However, for now, there is nothing wrong with this strategy. }
6. d3
{ Protecting the e4-pawn and opening up the diagonal for the dark-squared bishop. }
6... Bxc3
{ There might be no other chance to double White's pawns on the c-file, as the knight from c3 was ready to go to e2. }
7. bxc3 d6 { Preparing to develop the last light piece, the bishop from c8. }
8. Re1 { White protects the e4-pawn, thus preparing d4. } 8... Bd7
{ An interesting, rare move with the simple idea of being able to recapture on c6 with the bishop, for example, after  9.Rb1  , we'll play  9...a6  , asking White's bishop a serious question.   The mainline is  8...a6  where after  9.Bxc6  bxc6  , the position is balanced. }
9. a4
{ Preparing a way for the light-squared bishop to retreat after a potential a6. }
9... h6 { Prophylaxis against  10.Bg5  . } 10. a5
{ Trying to bother us by means of a6.  10.d4  would lead to positions similar to the mainline. }
10... Ne7 11. Bc4
{ Keeping the bishops on the board doesn't work so well with White's pawn being on a5. }
11... b5
{ Forcing the pawns to trade, as after  12.Bb3  c5  , the a5-pawn will become weak, forcing White's rook to stay on its initial square to protect it, while the bishop on b3 might also feel uncomfortable because of potential c4 threats. }
12. axb6 axb6 13. Rxa8 Qxa8
{ Black is better thanks to the control of the a-file and superior pawn structure. Notice how our queen eyes the e4-pawn, making it impossible for White to push d4. We can continue by finishing our knight rerouting to g6, after which we can take space on the queenside by means of c5, b5. }
