{ 13...dxe5  would lose material after  14.Bxf6  . } 13... axb5
{ 14.Bxf6  gxf6  would most likely transpose. } 14. Nxd7 Qxd7 15. Bxf6 gxf6
{ Let's take a look at the position.  • Both sides have a damaged pawn structure - White's doubled c-pawns and a2-pawn are weak, while Black has the doubled f-pawns and the h6 one to worry about.  • However, if we compare them, we notice an important difference, unlike Black's h6-pawn, White's a2 one is on an open file, where it can easily be attacked by the enemy's heavy pieces.  • The e4-pawn is also a target.  Due to these facts, Black is better. We can continue by bringing our rook to e5, then double on the e-file, or use the rook to bother White's weak pawns. }
