[White "7) 4.Qe2 & 4.d4 Lines "]
[Black "4.d4 exd4 5.Nxd4"]
[Result "*"]

{ With long variations to remember which still end with equality in the mainlines, the sidelines are becoming an often guest at both top level, and in our own mortals' games.This is the reason why I recommend paying by no means less attention when studying them. It is very likely that you'll encounter them more often than the mainlines. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d4
{ The most direct way to try posing Black problems. White wants to open up the centre and create threats against our king. }
4... exd4 5. Nxd4 Nxe4
{ We have just enough time to collect the juicy, central pawn. } 6. O-O Nxd4 7.
Qxd4
{ Attacking our knight and planning on occupying the e-file with the rook. }
7... Nc5
{ We need to have the option of covering our king by means of ...Ne6 in order to avoid our king getting in serious trouble. }
8. Re1+ Ne6 9. Nd2
{ There are not enough pieces around our king to create serious threats, therefore White tries to bring some more. }
9... c6
{ The easiest—we prepare playing d5, while also attacking White's bishop. } 10.
Bd3 d5 11. Nf3 Qf6
{ With a balanced position. White should trade queens and hope to have enough counterplay for the sacrificed pawn in the endgame, which, with some precision, is indeed the case. Shall White avoid the queen trade- we'll simply finish our development by means of  12.--  Be7  ,  13.--  O-O  and enjoy the extra pawn. }
