[Result "*"]

{ With long variations to remember which still end with equality in the mainlines, the sidelines are becoming an often guest at both top level, and in our own mortals' games.This is the reason why I recommend paying by no means less attention when studying them. It is very likely that you'll encounter them more often than the mainlines. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d4
{ The most direct way to try posing Black problems. White wants to open up the centre and create threats against our king. }
4... exd4 5. e5
{ Making our knight decide where it wants to go. Usually, the Ne4-c5 route is the best. }
5... Ne4
{ Taking on d4 now with  6.Nxd4  is dangerous in view of  6...Bc5  and White will have a problem with their f2-pawn.   The developmental  6.Qe2  will be met by  6...Nc5  . }
6. O-O a6
{ A very important move. White's bishop is surprisingly well-placed on b5, so we need it on a different square. Interestingly, all the available options have some drawbacks. Both,  7.Bd3  and  7.Ba4  gets under tempo after  7...Nc5  . }
7. Bxc6 { The only way for White to get their pawn back right away. } 7... dxc6
{ Capturing with the d-pawn is what we do in almost all of the cases when White takes our knight on c6. We do so to open up our light-squared bishop. }
8. Nxd4
{ White gets their pawn back, but losses the advantage in development. } 8...
Bc5
{ When possible, we should develop our pieces with a tempo, as here. We attack the knight on d4 while getting ready to castle short. }
9. Be3 O-O { Our king has reached a haven. } 10. Qd3 Bxd4 11. Bxd4 Bf5
{ Our development is completed. We are slightly better thanks to White's potential weakness of the e5-pawn, which we can exploit by b6, c5, thus pushing White's bishop away from protecting the e5-pawn. We can then put pressure on the lonely pawn through Qe7. }
