[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) 4.Qe2 & 4.d4 Lines "]
[Black "4.d4 exd4 5.O-O a6 6.Bc4"]
[Result "*"]

{ With long variations to remember which still end with equality in the mainlines, the sidelines are becoming an often guest at both top level, and in our own mortals' games.This is the reason why I recommend paying by no means less attention when studying them. It is very likely that you'll encounter them more often than the mainlines. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d4
{ The most direct way to try posing Black problems. White wants to open up the centre and create threats against our king. }
4... exd4 5. O-O
{ The most popular and best scoring move for White:  • They bring their king to safety, and introduces the idea of using the e-pawn to bother our knight on f6.  • They now also have the option of Rf1-Re1 up their sleeve. }
5... a6
{ Once again, we challenge White's bishop, making it go to a worse position, where it will get under tempi. It is very important to remember this idea, as otherwise, we might not be in time to finish our development under favourable circumstances.  The tarde  6.Bxc6  leads to a better position for us after  6...dxc6  thanks to the pair of bishops. }
6. Bc4 { Allows us to take the e4-pawn. } 6... Nxe4 7. Re1
{ This pin usually means trouble, however- not here, as we have the text move at our disposal! }
7... d5
{ A great move with a double purpose- protecting the knight and attacking White's bishop. Notice how important it is that we've forced White's bishop away from b5 so it now got under tempi.  White can't lose any more time by retreating their bishop again with something like  8.Bd3  , as after  8...Bb4  , we'll be in full control of the position and with an extra pawn! }
8. Bxd5 { White uses a tactical idea in order to get their pawn back. } 8...
Qxd5 9. Nc3
{ Due to the pin along the e-file, we cannot capture the c3-knight; therefore, White will win their material back. }
9... Qa5
{ 10.Rxe4+  would be still met by  10...Be6  and  11.--  O-O-O  , where Black will be significantly better thanks to the better piece harmony and control in the centre, while also being, if only temporary, but still a pawn up. }
10. Nxe4 Be6 11. Neg5 { Aiming to get the pawn back after capturing on e6. }
11... O-O-O 12. Nxe6 fxe6 13. Rxe6
{ White got their pawn back, which is good news for them, but not good enough, as there's no more than equality for them to hope for. }
13... Be7
{ We are first to complete our development and will continue with a central strategy, by improving the position of our pieces with  14.--  Qd5  and then Rh8-Rf8. Thanks to this plan of action, we can hope to overtake. }
