8. Bb3 d6
{ Opening up the bishop, while also stopping White from pushing the e-pawn. }
9. a4
{ White attacks our queenside, hoping to either win the b5-pawn for free or force it to move forward- which would weaken the light squares around it. }
9... Bg4
{ A good developing move. We pin White's knight, so it can't recapture our d4-pawn anymore, while also connecting the queen to the rook on a8. }
10. axb5 axb5 11. Rxa8 Qxa8 12. c3
{ White wants to either capture on d4, or develop the knight to c3- if we take the pawn on c3. }
12... Qa5
{ Black is better thanks to the extra pawn.  With our last move, we stopped White from playing  13.cxd4  given  13...Bxf3  14.gxf3  Nxd4  , taking advantage that White's queen can't recapture on d4, as their rook on e1 is hanging. }
