{ White hopes that by retreating the bishop to a4, they will not have to lose tempi due to potential attacks on the light-squared bishop. However, it is clear that the text move is a compromise than the bishop going to c4, as it is currently less active and does not enjoy the same prospects. }
6... Be7
{ We simply continue with our development, preparing to short castle. It would have given White more possibilities if we had done it on the previous move.   With their bishop on b5 rather than a4, they could use it on the f1-a6 diagonal - an option that they no longer have.   Chess is a game where limiting our opponent's possibilities is often more important than executing our own plans. }
7. Re1
{ The most natural. White not only protects the e4-pawn, but also prepares to push it by means of  7...--  8.e5  , where our knight will no longer have the e4-square at its disposal. }
7... b5
{ Playing against White's light-squared bishop is an important part of our plan. We force it further and also take away the possibility of White capturing on c6. }
8. Bb3 d6
{ Opening up the bishop, while also stopping White from pushing the e-pawn. }
9. Bd5 { Creating a pin which we can't tolerate. } 9... Nxd5 10. exd5 Ne5
{ White has given up on the pair of bishops in order to get back the sacrificed pawn. They now have a choice- take on d4 or on e5. }
11. Nxe5 { Leads to a lost position for White. } 11... dxe5 12. Rxe5 O-O
{ Black has a decisive advantage, as the d4-pawn is untouchable in view of  13.Qxd4  Bf6  , while White's d5-pawn will be lost after we make White's rook go away by means of the same Bf6. }
