{ Bringing the king to safety is always a good idea! } 12. a4
{ A typical move to fight against our expanded queenside pawn structure, hoping to create some weaknesses in our camp. }
12... Bg4
{ Once again, we finish the development with tempi, attacking White's queen.  13.f3  will weaken the a7-g1 diagonal and we can simply meet it by  13...Bd7  , with c6/c5 ideas. }
13. Qd2
{ White's queen on d2 is badly placed , as it stands in the way of the dark-squared bishop. }
13... Bd7
{ Once we've forced White's queen to move to a suboptimal square, the bishop has finished its job on g4 and can return to protect the pawn on b5. }
14. Nc3 { White increases the pressure against the b5-pawn. } 14... b4
{ White's knight is well placed on c3, so we force it away.  15.Nce2  can be met by  15...Qb8  , protecting the b4-pawn and aiming to attack White's d5- pawn by means of  16.--  Qb7  . }
15. Ne4 Qb8
{ The queen will feel very comfortable on b7, from where it both protects, b4 and attacks d5. }
16. f4 { White fights against our centrally placed knight. } 16... Ng4
{ The best square for our knight, as it's en route to f6, from where we'll attack the d5-pawn. }
17. h3 Nf6 { 18.--  Nxd5  is a serious threat. } 18. c4
{ The best way to protect the d5-pawn. } 18... bxc3 19. Nxc3 Re8
{ Black is somewhat better thanks to the pair of bishops and better harmony between pieces.  We'll continue by applying pressure on the d5-pawn by means of  20.--  Qb7  and then we can fight for the e-file by means of Bf8. }
