9. Nf5 { The only way for White to avoid us getting the pair of bishops. } 9...
d5
{ Highlighting the downside of White's previous move, by leaving with their knight, they took the pressure off the c6-square, allowing us to open up our light-squared bishop with a tempi. }
10. Nxe7+ Nxe7 11. c3
{ Making room for the bishop to retreat on c2. White is the one who enjoys the pair of bishops, but not for long. }
11... Nc5 12. Bc2 Bf5
{ Leaving White no choice but to part with their newly acquired 2 bishops trump. }
13. Na3 Qd7 14. Be3 Ne6
{ The best square for our knight, as it will nicely support the d4-push.   The love  15.Bb3  , trying to keep the pair of bishops is too slow, as after  15...Rad8  ,  16.--  d4  will follow- with our e6-knight likely to then land on d4, where it will be by no means inferior to any of White's bishops. }
15. f4
{ White has a pawn majority on the kingside, thus using it by taking space on that side of the board makes perfect sense. They hope to be able to push 16.g4, followed by 17.f5. }
15... f6 { Challenging White's nice centre right away. } 16. exf6 Rxf6
{ White's f4-pawn has now become a target for the Black forces to aim for. We'll continue doubling our rooks on the f-file, while our queen can join the party from d6. Black is better. }
