{ The best square for our knight, as it will nicely support the d4-push.   The move  15.Bb3  , trying to keep the pair of bishops is too slow, as after  15.--  Rad8  ,  16.--  d4  will follow- with our e6-knight likely to then land on d4, where it will be by no means inferior to any of White's bishops. }
15. g4
{ Forcing us to trade bishops.  The move  15...Bg6  would be a mistake, as after  16.f4  we don't have a good way to stop the incoming f5-push. }
15... Bxc2 16. Nxc2 f5
{ The best way to stop White's pawn advance on the kingside. } 17. exf6 Rxf6
{ Aiming for the weak f4-square. } 18. f4
{ Threatening to play  18...--  19.f5  . } 18... g6
{ With a complicated, yet balanced position.   We've successfully stopped White from playing f5 and plan to double our rooks on the f-file, increasing the pressure against the f4-pawn.   We should also keep in mind the idea of a breakthrough in the centre by means of d4. }
