[White "7) 4.Qe2 & 4.d4 Lines "]
[Black "4.d4 exd4 5.O-O a6 6.Ba4 #14"]
[Result "*"]

{ With long variations to remember which still end with equality in the mainlines, the sidelines are becoming an often guest at both top level, and in our own mortals' games.This is the reason why I recommend paying by no means less attention when studying them. It is very likely that you'll encounter them more often than the mainlines. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d4
{ The most direct way to try posing Black problems. White wants to open up the centre and create threats against our king. }
4... exd4 5. O-O
{ The most popular and best scoring move for White:  • They bring their king to safety, and introduces the idea of using the e-pawn to bother our knight on f6.  • They now also have the option of Rf1-Re1 up their sleeve. }
5... a6
{ Once again, we challenge White's bishop, making it go to a worse position, where it will get under tempi. It is very important to remember this idea, as otherwise, we might not be in time to finish our development under favourable circumstances.  The tarde  6.Bxc6  leads to a better position for us after  6...dxc6  thanks to the pair of bishops. }
6. Ba4
{ White hopes that by retreating the bishop to a4, they will not have to lose tempi due to potential attacks on the light-squared bishop. However, it is clear that the text move is a compromise than the bishop going to c4, as it is currently less active and does not enjoy the same prospects. }
6... Be7
{ We simply continue with our development, preparing to short castle. It would have given White more possibilities if we had done it on the previous move.   With their bishop on b5 rather than a4, they could use it on the f1-a6 diagonal - an option that they no longer have.   Chess is a game where limiting our opponent's possibilities is often more important than executing our own plans. }
7. e5
{ The most straightforward, taking space in the centre and forcing Black's knight to decide where it wants to land. }
7... Ne4
{ As usual, we want to be able to bring our knight to c5, from where it will bother White's bishop. }
8. Nxd4
{ The most natural- getting back the pawn and threatening to put pressure on the kingside by means of Nf5.   Black doesn't have time to go for the pair of bishops by means of  8...Nc5  given  9.Nf5  , sacrificing the bishop on a4, but aiming to get to our king after capturing on g7. }
8... O-O
{ Taking on c6.   The trade  9.Nxc6  dxc6  will lead to a favourable position for Black, as we'll either get the pair of bishops by means of  10.--  Nc5  , or trade the queens and head to a better endgame after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1pp1bppp/p1p5/4P3/B3n3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.c3  Qxd1  , where White will have trouble with the weak d3-square. }
9. Nf5 { The only way for White to avoid us getting the pair of bishops. } 9...
d5
{ Highlighting the downside of White's previous move, by leaving with their knight, they took pressure off the c6- square, allowing us to open up our light-squared bishop with a tempi. }
10. Bxc6
{ Going for a superior pawn structure, as we have no choice but to double our c-pawns. }
10... bxc6
{ It is interesting to notice that the doubled pawns aren't a disadvantage here as White can't either create threats against them or use the squares in front of them as a forepost. At the same time, the c6-pawn nicely defends its brother on d5. }
11. Nxe7+ Qxe7 { Little guy on e5, hanging! } 12. Re1
{ Indirectly protects the e5-pawn, as after  12...Qxe5  Black loses a piece after  13.f3  . }
12... Bf5
{ Finishing the development of our minor pieces. The turn for the heavy pieces to come to play comes next. }
13. f3 { Making Black's most active piece go away. } 13... Nc5 14. b3
{ Making the serious threat of  14...--  15.Ba3  , which would mean trouble for us, as the pin against the knight and queen would be deadly. }
14... Ne6
{ As we already know by now- this is the best square for our knight if e4 isn't available. }
15. Ba3 c5 16. Qxd5 { Taking the pawn runs into a curious double attack. }
16... Qh4
{ The rook on e1 is under fire, while  17.--  Qd4  is also a very unpleasant threat. Don't forget that the c2-pawn is also left to our mercy.   17.Nc3  runs into  17...Rfd8  , followed by a check on d4, after which we could capture the c2-pawn. }
17. g3 { Stops only one of the 2 critical threats. } 17... Qd4+ 18. Qxd4 Nxd4
{ Black is winning, as White doesn't have a way to stop us from capturing on c2 with the knight. }
