[Black "4.Qe2 Bc5 5.O-O O-O 6.Bxc6 "]
[Result "*"]

{ With long variations to remember which still end with equality in the mainlines, the sidelines are becoming an often guest at both top level, and in our own mortals' games.This is the reason why I recommend paying by no means less attention when studying them. It is very likely that you'll encounter them more often than the mainlines. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. Qe2
{ The best scoring move. The idea is to protect the e4-pawn without committing the pawn to d3, thus keeping the possibility of playing c3, d4 in one go. }
4... Bc5
{ The best square for our bishop as it fights against potential d4 ideas. } 5.
O-O { Bringing the king to safety first. } 5... O-O 6. Bxc6
{ Let's see what happens if White tries once again to win our central pawn. }
6... bxc6
{ 6...dxc6  would actually work here as well, but I believe it's just easier to remember that once White's queen is on e2 we recapture with the b-pawn in order to place our light squared bishop on the a6-f1 diagonal. }
7. Nxe5 Qe8
{ Why e8? In order for our c6-pawn to be protected when we'll play d7-d6. } 8.
Nf3 Qxe4 9. Qxe4 Nxe4 10. d4 Bb6
{ With a balanced position, as we have the pair of bishops as a form of compensation for our somewhat damaged pawn structure.   It is important to avoid pushing our d-pawn to d5, as it would weaken the c5-square. Instead, we can first reroute our knight to f5 via d6, and then our pawn can occupy the same d6-square. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
