{ The best scoring move. The idea is to protect the e4-pawn without committing the pawn to d3, thus keeping the possibility of playing c3, d4 in one go. }
4... Bc5
{ The best square for our bishop as it fights against potential d4 ideas. } 5.
Bxc6 { A cunning move, as Black needs to react in an unusual way. } 5... bxc6
{ The only good way to recapture! It is vital to remember this move. As a suggestion - let's try to think like this - if White's queen is on e2 - we want to have the a6-f1 diagonal available for our bishop to disturb White's queen, thus our capturing with the b-pawn. }
6. Nxe5 Qe7 7. Nd3 Ba6
{ See how useful the newly opened diagonal is? As White's knight is now pinned, can will be able to capture the e4-pawn with our knight. }
8. Nc3 O-O
{ We have full compensation for the sacrificed pawn, as our bishops are monsters and White is really behind with their development. We can increase the pressure against the e4-pawn by bringing our rook from a8 to e8, with the d5-break as an additional resource. }
