[Black "4.Qe2 Bc5 5.c3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

{ With long variations to remember which still end with equality in the mainlines, the sidelines are becoming an often guest at both top level, and in our own mortals' games.This is the reason why I recommend paying by no means less attention when studying them. It is very likely that you'll encounter them more often than the mainlines. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. Qe2
{ The best scoring move. The idea is to protect the e4-pawn without committing the pawn to d3, thus keeping the possibility of playing c3, d4 in one go. }
4... Bc5
{ The best square for our bishop as it fights against potential d4 ideas. } 5.
c3
{ The most played and best scoring move for White. They are getting ready to play d4. }
5... O-O
{ Black brings the king to safety and will look for ways to finish their development. }
6. O-O
{ It is played more often than the alternative -  6.d3  ,  but it doesn't have a score that is too impressive, as White still needs one more move to prepare d4. }
6... Re8
{ We protect the e5-pawn with the rook rather than the pawn @@StartBracket@@with 6...d6@@EndBracket@@, because we want to keep in mind ideas of d5, taking control of the centre.   For example,  7.Rd1  will be met by  7...d5  . }
7. d3 { White aims to develop their minor pieces. } 7... a6
{ It is always useful to ask this bishop a question - where does it want to retreat to? }
8. Ba4 d5
{ Opening up our light-squared bishop and taking control of the centre.   The trades  9.exd5  Nxd5  works in our favour, as we have better development and more space. }
9. Bg5
{ White pins our knight, thus creating the unpleasant threat of taking on d5. }
9... dxe4 10. dxe4 h6 { Asking White's second bishop a question. } 11. Bh4 g5
{ A typical way to fight against White's dark-squared bishop.   The move  12.Nxg5  doesn't work given  12...hxg5  13.Bxg5  Bg4  , and White has no way of getting their piece back. }
12. Rd1 Qe7 13. Bxc6
{ Damaging our pawn structure comes at a too high cost- us getting the pair of bishops. }
13... bxc6 14. Bg3 Nh5
{ We are significantly better thanks to our pair of bishops. The light-squared one will come to life after a5, Ba6, while the dark one is already nicely placed. The knight will jump to f4, where if captured, we'll take back with the e-pawn, preparing to put pressure on White's e4-pawn. }
*

