[Result "*"]

{ With long variations to remember which still end with equality in the mainlines, the sidelines are becoming an often guest at both top level, and in our own mortals' games.This is the reason why I recommend paying by no means less attention when studying them. It is very likely that you'll encounter them more often than the mainlines. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. Qe2
{ The best scoring move. The idea is to protect the e4-pawn without committing the pawn to d3, thus keeping the possibility of playing c3, d4 in one go. }
4... Bc5
{ The best square for our bishop as it fights against potential d4 ideas. } 5.
c3
{ The most played and best scoring move for White. They are getting ready to play d4. }
5... O-O
{ Black brings the king to safety and will look for ways to finish their development. }
6. d3
{ The best scoring move in the position, though for no particular reason, as the resulting positions are very similar to the ones we've already examined. }
6... h6
{ Stopping White's bishop from developing to g5.   A pawn aggression through  7.g4  is premature - we will simply take it -  7...Nxg4  ,  attacking the f2-pawn. }
7. O-O Re8
{ We continue by protecting the e5-pawn and preparing the d5-push.   Both moves,  8.Nbd2  and  8.h3  , will be met by the promised  8...d5  . }
8. Be3 { Aiming for a bishop trade, while continuing the development. } 8...
Bf8
{ We prefer to avoid trading bishops, as after  8...Bxe3  9.fxe3  , White would get some play over the newly opened f-file. At the same time, we are once again ready to take control of the centre with d5. }
9. c4 { The only way to stop us from pushing our d-pawn to the 5th rank. } 9...
Ne7
{ Our knight had no prospects on c6, so it leaves for better 'pastures'. It is en route to g6, while the c6-square will be used by our pawn to prepare the d5-push. }
10. Nxe5 { Taking the central pawn is dangerous. } 10... c6 11. Ba4 Qa5
{ With a double attack on the e5-knight and a4-bishop, White has no better option than parting with one of them. }
12. Nxf7 Kxf7 13. Nc3 d6
{ White has decent compensation for the sacrificed piece, but they are yet to prove that it is enough for equality.   The advance  14.f4  will be met by  14...Kg8  , after which we can look for activity with b5. }
*

