9. c4 { The only way to stop us from pushing our d-pawn to the 5th rank. } 9...
Ne7
{ Our knight had no prospects on c6, so it leaves for better 'pastures'. It is en route to g6, while the c6-square will be used by our pawn to prepare the d5-push. }
10. Ba4 { Prophylaxis against c6. } 10... c6
{ We open the diagonal for our queen to land on a5 if needed. } 11. h3 Ng6
{ Protecting the e5-pawn. } 12. Nc3 d6
{ With White's bishop still on a4, our rook on e8 is pinned, so we couldn't go for the d5-break. However, the more modest d6 works well enough.   We opened the c8-h3 diagonal for our bishop, and we can continue by playing Nh5-Nhf4, while the queen can go to f6 creating various threats against White's king. A piece sacrifice on h3 should be kept in mind. The position is balanced. }
