[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) 4.O-O Nxe4 5.Re1 & Others"]
[Black "4.O-O Nxe4 5.Re1 Nd6 6.Bxc6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. Re1
{ The second most popular move after  5.d4  . White aims for a symmetrical position where they will try to use their advantage in development. }
5... Nd6
{ A retreat with tempo, attacking the bishop on b5. White will have several continuations to choose from. }
6. Bxc6 { Giving up the pair of bishops can't be good. } 6... dxc6
{ As in most cases, we recapture on c6 with the d-pawn in order to open the diagonal for the light-squared bishop. }
7. Nxe5 Be7 { We simply continue our development, aiming to castle short. } 8.
d4 O-O 9. Bf4
{ 9.c4  would be met by the same reaction as 9. Bf4,  i.e.  9...Re8  , where the line could continue  10.Nc3  Bf8  ,  preparing to push back White’s knight from e5 by means of f6, after which we’ll build up pressure against the d4-pawn. We can achieve it by developing the bishop to e6 and then bringing the queen to d7 and the rook from a to d8. }
9... Re8
{ Since the e-file is the only open file, we should establish control over it. }
10. Nd2 Bf8 11. c3
{ Asks White’s knight an unpleasant question, where to retreat to? } 11... f6
12. Nef3 Be6
{ Taking the b3-square away from White’s queen, while continuing the development. }
13. a4
{ White can try the marginal pawn push, hoping to be able to grab some extra space. }
13... a5 { There is no need to allow White’s pawn to advance further. } 14. Nf1
{ White could try bringing their knight to g3 in the hope of creating some threats on the kingside. }
14... Qd7 { Now that the rooks are connected- the development is finished. }
15. Ng3 Bf7
{ A rook trade over the e-file is convenient for Black, as White will have trouble bringing their other rook to the open e-file because they might run into trouble with their a4-pawn, which could be bothered by our bishop by playing Bb3, if the white queen will leave the d1-a4 diagonal. Overall, Black is better thanks to the pair of bishops, which make it easy for us to play on both flanks, combining ideas of Bb3, Nc4, and even h5. }
*

