10. Nd2 Bf8 11. c3 f6 12. Nec4
{ White can only hope to maintain the balance, as several trades will follow. }
12... Nxc4 13. Rxe8 Qxe8 14. Nxc4 Be6
{ Our bishop bothers White’s knight while also eyeing the a2-pawn. } 15. Ne3
Qd7
{ The position is balanced, though I would still prefer Black thanks to the pair of bishops, as they are long-range pieces that can be used effectively when the battle takes place on both flanks.   An interesting plan would be to continue by placing our bishop on f7 - a flexible square from which it still keeps an eye on the queenside, while also being able to move to the b1-h7 diagonal if needed. Next, the rook will come to the center, most likely to the d8-square, after which we can consider a pawn expansion on the queenside with a7-a5 and/or b7-b5. }
