[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. Re1
{ The second most popular move after  5.d4  . White aims for a symmetrical position where they will try to use their advantage in development. }
5... Nd6
{ A retreat with tempo, attacking the bishop on b5. White will have several continuations to choose from. }
6. a4
{ An interesting move played by many top grandmasters. The idea is simple- protect the bishop and get ready to recapture on b5 with the pawn. }
6... Be7
{ As always, we continue our development, planning to castle short. Taking on b5 would be a bad idea, as after  6...Nxb5  7.axb5  , our knight on c6 will have to answer unpleasant questions. }
7. Nxe5
{ White can take their pawn back, but it will lead to a pleasant position for us. }
7... Nxe5 8. Rxe5 O-O
{ Our king is safe and the next step will be to finish the development of the queenside. }
9. Nc3 c6 10. Bf1 Ne8
{ Black's position is slightly more pleasant, as we'll continue pushing d5, opening a path for our light-squared bishop, while the knight will jump to f6.  There is more harmony between our pieces which will work very well together, unlike White's pieces. The knight on c3 doesn't have great prospects, as it's limited by the c6-pawn and the rook on e5 is a target. }
