1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. Re1
{ The second most popular move after  5.d4  . White aims for a symmetrical position where they will try to use their advantage in development. }
5... Nd6
{ A retreat with tempo, attacking the bishop on b5. White will have several continuations to choose from. }
6. Nxe5
{ The mainline. The bishop on b5 is untouchable given  6...Nxb5  7.Nxc6+  , where Black loses the queen. }
6... Be7
{ Covering the e-file and planning to castle short after White deals with the imminent threat of  7.--  Nxb5  . }
7. Bf1 Nxe5 8. Rxe5 O-O
{ Once again, our king is safe and we can focus on completing the development of our queenside. }
9. d4 Bf6
{ We need White's rook to go away as it covers the f5-square which we want to use for our knight. }
10. Re2
{ Is a rather mysterious-looking move. In an equal position, White tries to muddy the waters. There is no particular difference compared to  10.Re1  , only that here we have the additional option of playing b6, which threatens Ba6. }
10... b6 11. Re1
{ It is indeed a loss of tempo, but White wants to argue that b6 might have been a weakening of our pawn structure- which isn't the case. }
11... Bb7 12. Bf4 Nf5 { White needs to protect their d4-pawn. } 13. c3 Re8
{ The simplest way towards equality is trading as many pieces as possible. }
14. Rxe8+ Qxe8
{ 15.Bxc7  is bad in view of  15...d6  , when White's bishop on c7 will be trapped. }
15. Nd2 d6 16. Qc2 Nh4 { The knight is just fine on h4. } 17. Bg3 Ng6
{ With a balanced position. We can continue by pushing h5, bothering White's dark-squared bishop, then double on the e-file by means of Qe6, and Re8. }
*

