[Result "*"]

{ Other than going for the Endgame line, White has a few other moves they can try, which cause no major troubles for us, though some precision is still needed to equalize comfortably. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6
{ Black has created the threat of taking on b5, thus White has a few options in dealing with it other than going for the Endgame Line after  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.dxe5  Nf5  . }
6. Ba4
{ The 3rd most popular move in the position and the most natural bishop retreat. Still, it involves a pawn sacrifice we will gladly accept. }
6... exd4
{ Taking the offered pawn, leaving it to White to prove their compensation.   The check,  7.Re1+  would be met by  7...Be7  , where after  8.c3  , there will be a transposition to the following line. }
7. c3
{ White doesn't recapture on d4 and is prepared to play with 2 pawns down instead.   We can afford taking on  c3  , as after  7...dxc3  8.Re1+  Be7  9.Nxc3  O-O  10.Nd5  , White will have fantastic compensation for their pawns thanks to their piece activity, leaving us on the verge of losing. }
7... Be7
{ Simply continuing the development and aiming to bring our king to safety by castling short is the best option. }
8. cxd4 O-O
{ The king is safe.   Our next step will be finding a way to develop our light-squared bishop. }
9. d5 b5 { A nice counterattacking resource! } 10. Bc2
{ Doesn't really avoid the bishop hunt. } 10... Nb4 11. Bb3 a5
{ Threatening on playing  12.--  a4  , leaving White's bishop no other choice than to agree to trade it for our knight. }
12. a3 Na6
{ A temporary retreat. Our knight will have the option of joining the party in the centre via the c5-quare. }
13. Bc2 Bf6
{ Black has a healthy extra pawn, while White faces difficulties in developing their queenside, as they have to deal with our dark-squared bishop eyeing the b2-pawn as well as with b4 threats in case they would develop the knight to c3.   At the same time, we don't have to worry about our kingside, as we'll always have the g6 resource should White create any threats on the b1-h7 diagonal, while we plan to push b4, place our bishop on b7 and then improve the position of our a6 knight- perhaps by bringing it to c5. }
