{ Other than going for the Endgame line, White has a few other moves they can try, which cause no major troubles for us, though some precision is still needed to equalize comfortably. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6
{ Black has created the threat of taking on b5, thus White has a few options in dealing with it other than going for the Endgame Line after  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.dxe5  Nf5  . }
6. Bg5 { The 4th most popular move, aiming for a fast development. } 6... Be7
7. Bxe7 Qxe7 { As always, we aim to bring our king to safety fast. } 8. dxe5
{ A typical temporary piece sacrifice. } 8... Nxb5 9. a4
{ Our knight has no way to avoid peril, but we can use the time White spends trapping it to finish our development. }
9... d6
{ Opening up our light-squared bishop while taking advantage of White's not being able to open the e-file by capturing on d6, as after  10.exd6  Nxd6  , we'll be a piece up. }
10. axb5 Nxe5
{ Once again, we're a pawn up!  Avoiding the knight trade by playing  11.Nd4  would be met by  11...O-O  , where White will have a very tough job proving any compensation for the sacrificed pawn. }
11. Nxe5 dxe5 12. Nc3 O-O
{ White is pawn down, but has compenation thanks to their active rook on the a-file and their superior knight to our bishop, which becomes even more obvious after the text move. We will have to be precise. }
13. Qf3
{ Not allowing us to finish the development, as our bishop must stay on c8, protecting the pawn on b7. }
13... a6
{ Provoking White to take the pawn, where after  14.bxa6  Rxa6  we will solve the issue of our weak pawn on b7 by either recapturing on a6 or pushing c6 after first trading rooks. }
14. Nd5 Qc5 { A double attack on the b5- and c2-pawns. } 15. b4
{ White sacrifices one more pawn in their quest for piece activity. The one on b5 is untouchable given the pawn on c7, while the same can't be said about the c2-pawn, which we could capture, but after  15...Qxc2  18.Rac1  , White would get easy play over the c-file. }
15... Qc4 { Keeping the matters closed on the 'c' file. } 16. Qd3 Qxd3 17. cxd3
Rd8
{ White will get their pawn back, but the position will simplify too much. }
18. Nxc7 Rb8 19. bxa6 bxa6 20. Nxa6 Bxa6 21. Rxa6 Rxb4
{ After a series of exchanges, we have an equal rook endgame where we even enjoy the upper hand thanks to the superior pawn structure. }
