{ White continues their development and threatens to jump with the knight to b5. In the same time, their queen keeps an eye on our a7-pawn, so that we can't castle long. }
14... a6
{ The best way to both stop the  15.Nb5  threat and solve the problem of the targeted a7-pawn. }
15. Rd1 Qc6
{ Our queen is comfortable on c6, as it targets the c2-pawn so that White's knight would have difficulties to move away from c3. }
16. Qg3
{ White eyes the g7-pawn, hoping that it would stop us from developing the dark-squared bishop, thus making our king to stay in the centre. }
16... Bd6
{ We sacrifice the g7-pawn in order to cover the d-file, enabling us to castle long. }
17. Qxg7 { Taking the pawn is very dangerous for White. } 17... O-O-O
{ Threatening to win the game after bringing a rook to the g-file. } 18. Qh6
Rdg8 { The pawn on g2 should now be very worried. } 19. g3 Bg4
{ Another tempo move, attacking White's rook and highlighting the weakness of the light squares in White's camp. }
20. Re1 Rg6 { The poor queen, doesn't enjoy a vast choice. } 21. Qd2 Re8
{ With a significant advantage for Black, as White's king is in great danger because of the weakened light squares around it and White's being behind with their development- their bishop and rook from a1 still need quite some time in order to enter the game.   On the other hand, our pieces are all playing and looking at White's king. The 2nd rook will join the party on the e-file, while our light-squared bishop may choose from the h3 or f3 squares. }
