{ Other than going for the Endgame line, White has a few other moves they can try, which cause no major troubles for us, though some precision is still needed to equalize comfortably. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6
{ Black has created the threat of taking on b5, thus White has a few options in dealing with it other than going for the Endgame Line after  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.dxe5  Nf5  . }
6. dxe5
{ The 2nd most popular continuation after  6.Bxc6  .   White temporarily sacrifices a piece. }
6... Nxb5 7. a4
{ Our knight on b5 can't be saved, but we can choose on which square White will capture it. }
7... Nbd4
{ By placing our knight here, we avoid White's opening up the a-file for their rook after they would capture our knight on b5. }
8. Nxd4 d5
{ We are in time to immediately open the diagonal for our light-squared bishop. }
9. exd6
{ The mainline, White opens up the e-file, hoping to be able to create threats against our king. }
9... Nxd4 10. Qxd4 Qxd6
{ A queen trade would favour Black, as we have the pair of bishops and king safety won't be an issue anymore if entering an endgame. }
11. Qe4+ Qe6 { Another check- another queen's trade offer. } 12. Qd4 Qd6
{ The famous Berlin Draw by perpetual check. White may choose to keep on playing by delivering a check on e3. }
13. Qe3+
{ The idea is that now, after the typical  13...Qe6  , White has  14.Qg3  , targeting our c7- and g7-pawns, thus not allowing us time to comfortably finish our development. }
13... Be6
{ Taking advantage that White's queen isn't on e4, targeting our b7-pawn. } 14.
Nc3
{ White continues their development and threatens to jump with the knight to b5. In the same time, their queen keeps an eye on our a7-pawn, so that we can't castle long. }
14... a6
{ The best way to both stop the  15.Nb5  threat and solve the problem of the targeted a7-pawn. }
15. Rd1 Qc6
{ Our queen is comfortable on c6, as it targets the c2-pawn so that White's knight would have difficulties to move away from c3. }
16. Rd3
{ White hopes for us to play  16...Bd6  , where after  17.Nb5!  , they would gain a tempo, as we'd have to retreat with our bishop. }
16... Be7 { Preparing to castle short. } 17. Nb5
{ An interesting tactical resource, White creates the threat of a fork on d4, while tempting us to go for  17...axb5  , which is a bad idea, as after  18.axb5  , we can't avoid losing material, as both our queen and rook on a8 are hanging. }
17... Bc4 { Double attack! } 18. Rd1
{ Inviting us to capture on b5 once again.   The trade  18...axb5  doesn't work for the same reason as one move before, while  18...Bxb5  19.axb5  Qxb5  is dangerous because after  20.b3  , White will have great compensation for their pawn, as our king is stuck in the centre. }
18... Rd8 { An elegant way to solve all of our problems. } 19. Rxd8+ Kxd8
{ Our king is safe in the centre with a pair of rooks gone, as White's a1-rook has to go quite a long way in order to get to the d-file. }
20. Nd4 Qd7
{ A simple retreat does the job. Our king can walk to c8 if needed, while our rook wants to come to the open e-file as soon as possible. }
21. Qc3 Bd5
{ The best possible square for our bishop, as it controls all of the board, taking special interest in White's g2-pawn. }
22. Nf3 { White has made the unsubtle threat of capturing our g7-pawn. } 22...
Qf5
{ We had many ways to proceed, but this looks like the most dangerous one for White. We sacrifice a pawn in order to play for the initiative. }
23. Qxg7 Re8
{ There are many unpleasant threats White has to cope with.   • First of all, the weakness of their back rank.  • Secondly, the knight on f3 is hanging   • Last, but not least, the c2-pawn is also under fire. }
24. Be3 { Solving a part of the problems. } 24... Bxf3 25. gxf3 h5
{ With a balanced position, but one where White is the one who has to be really careful not to get in trouble.   Our king will be much safer on c8 than the White one, while White's extra pawn has no value as it is doubled on the f-file. We will continue to create threats against White's weaknesses, the f3-pawn in particular and the h2-pawn, by means of Bd6. }
