[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Kasparov, G. vs. Kramnik, V. (2000)"]
[Result "*"]

{ What would be a Berlin course without a game from the Kasparov-Kramnik, World Championship Match? }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5
8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Nc3 h6
{ If in the first game of their match, Kramnik chose  9...Bd7  which was entirely new at the time, with the idea of bringing the king to the queenside and later employed it again, successfully holding draws in both games. Here he switched to what was considered to be the standard approach at that time, keeping the king on the kingside, not wanting to test what Kasparov's team came up with against the Bd7, Kc8 setup.   In the course, we choose a somewhat different approach, going for the immediate  9...Be7  , with the idea of offering a knight trade by means of Nh4. There are, however, some similarities between these 2 lines - in both of them, Black's king ends up usually on the kingside. }
10. Rd1+
{ White loses some flexibility with this check. He later will have to move the rook again to bring out the rook from a1. }
10... Ke8
{ Isn't possible  10...Bd7??  11.g4!  forcing away the knight.  11...Ne7  12.e6!  fxe6  13.Ne5+-  the bishop on d7 is lost.   But not @@StartFEN@@r2k1b1r/pppb1pp1/2p4p/4Pn2/8/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BR2K1 w - - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11.e6??  fxe6  12.Ne5  Nd6=  Black saves the piece and keeps the balance. }
11. h3 { Kasparov prepares g4. } 11... a5
{ A typical, useful move, taking space on the queenside. } 12. Bf4
{ The optimal square for White's bishop, eyeing the c7-pawn. } 12... Be6
{ Taking away the e6 ideas from White.   The move  12...Be7?!  would be imprecise  13.e6!  Bxe6  14.Bxc7⩲  because White has an edge, as Black will struggle to get their h8-rook into the game. }
13. g4 Ne7 14. Nd4 Nd5
{ Best, not allowing White's bishop on g3 so easily.   The g6-square wouldn't be a good place for the knight because White has a significant advantage after  14...Ng6?  15.Bg3  h5  16.Nxe6  fxe6  17.Ne4±  thanks to their very good knight on e4 and the lack of counterplay for Black. }
15. Nce2
{ The move  15.Bg3?  doesn't work now.  15...Nxc3  16.bxc3  Bc4  Black is by no means worse with the pair of bishops and White's pawn structure on the queenside shattered.   The bishop move,  15.Bd2  , could lead to some interesting complications.  15...Nxc3  16.Nxe6!?  a nice intermediate move!  16...fxe6  17.Bxc3⩲  now White has a better endgame, though one might argue that it's just the better side of a draw. The position reminds me a lot of the one I got when playing vs GM Hamdouchi and I managed to hold my grounds @@StartBracket@@see the Hamdouchi-Bulmaga game, for more details@@EndBracket@@.   Taking on d1  16...Nxd1?  runs into trouble.  17.Nxc7+  Kd7  18.Nxa8  Nxf2  19.Nb6+!   If  19.Kxf2?  , White loses the advantage.  19...Bc5+=  19...Kc7  20.Nc4  Nxh3+  21.Kg2  21...Ng5  22.Rf1±  a nice touch! White doesn't hurry taking on a5 and instead creates yet another threat, to capture on g5 and then on f7. Black faces a very tough defence ahead. }
15... Bc5
{ Kramnik continues the development.   The trade  15...Nxf4?  would lead to a position where the pair of knights dominates the pair of bishops.  16.Nxf4  Bc8  17.Rd3±  Black will struggle to get his pieces into play. }
16. Nxe6 fxe6 17. c4 Nb6 18. b3
{ Kasparov plays against Kramnik's knight, limiting it as much as possible. }
18... a4 { Black doesn't lose time and goes for an attack on the queenside. }
19. Bd2 { Threatening to push the bishop away by means of b4. } 19... Kf7 20.
Bc3
{ The advance  20.b4  wouldn't achieve the desired result.  20...Be7  21.Rac1  Rhd8  Black has now ideas of infiltrating with the rook on the 3rd rank, which could even mean some chances for overtaking. }
20... Rhd8 { All of Black's pieces are now in play. } 21. Rxd8
{ The move  21.Kg2  was the alternative.  21...Be7  planning to reroute the knight to c5 after first taking on b3 and then on a1. The position is balanced. }
21... Rxd8 22. Kg2 Rd3 { The best square for the rook! } 23. Rc1 g5
{ Fixing White's pawns and taking away the f4-square from Kasparov's knight. }
24. Rc2 axb3 25. axb3 Nd7
{ The knight had nothing left to do on b6, so Kramnik seeks a better position for it. }
26. Ra2 Be7 27. Ra7 Nc5 28. f3
{ Kasparov simply covers the e4-square, deciding not to take any risks.   The advance  28.b4  could lead to some complications.  28...Ne4  29.Bd4  c5  30.Be3!   The trade  30.bxc5?  would be a mistake.  30...Bxc5  31.Bxc5  Nxc5⩱  Black protects the b7-pawn and enjoys a pleasant advantage thanks to White's weak pawns on c4 and e5.  30...cxb4  31.Rxb7  Ke8  with a double-edged position. The pawn on b4 can become dangerous. }
28... Nxb3 29. Rxb7 Nc1 30. Nxc1 Rxc3 31. Ne2 Rc2 32. Kf1 Rxc4 33. Rxc7
{ The players agreed to a draw, as there are no real chances for either of the sides.   Conclusions:   1. One should be careful not to play too passively, but rather go for counterplay whenever possible, even in the endgame.  2. Getting the pair of bishops is not a universal recipe to an advantage. Other particularities of the position should also be considered. }
