[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Hamdouchi, H. vs. Bulmaga, I. (2024)"]
[Result "*"]

{ A recent game I played in the last round of the Porticcio Open in Corsica. Playing versus an experienced GM, I decided to go for a solid approach, choosing the Berlin. The standindgs were so that I was sharing the 1st place, having quite good tie-breaks, which meant that a draw in this game could likely win me a top 3 place. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ I believe my opening choice came as a suprise to my opponent, as I have only opted for the Berlin once before in a classical game. }
4. O-O
{ A slight surprise to me, as in most of his recent games, my opponent went for the  4.d3  system, which I thought would be his try in this game as well, as it leads to long strategic battles.  He needed to try for a win in order to fight for a good prize because his tie-breaks were the worst among the group of players in the lead, so a long battle would suit his intentions best I thought. }
4... Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ Perhaps my opponent thought that the endgame line was worth a try, as I didn't have experience in it- this being the first time I played it with the Black pieces. }
9. Nc3 Be7 10. Bf4
{ In the course, I recommend 10...Be6  in this position, stopping any potential e6 ideas and preparing to walk with the king to the queendside in the event of a check on the d-file. Unfortunately, I didn't remember it during the game, so I went for the typical and most straightforward idea you encountered in the Endgame Line- the trade of knights via the h4-square, which isn't bad either. }
10... Nh4
{ Perhaps you can add this move to your arsenal as well. Compared to  10...Be6  , it is a more simplistic approach- aimed to dry out the position completely.  10...Be6  leads to richer positions, where Black can hope for more than a draw.   The development  10...Be6  11.Rad1+  Kc8∞  follows the line I recommend in the course, leading to a balanced position. }
11. Rad1+ Ke8
{ The move  11...Bd7??  would be a terrible mistake.  12.Nxh4  Bxh4  13.e6  fxe6  14.Ne4  Ke7  15.Rfe1+-  White has a decisive advantage thanks to their much better pieces. }
12. Nd4
{ The trade  12.Nxh4  Bxh4  13.Ne2  Be7  14.Nd4  would transpose to the game. }
12... Nf5 { Staying true to the idea of 'hunting' White's knight down. } 13.
Nce2 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Be6
{ I assessed the resulting endgame after White's capture on e6 as drawish and rightly so, though the engine thinks it wasn't necessary to go for this 'suffering'. It is true that by giving up the pair of bishops, I found myself in a position with no chances to win, but as stressed before- my plan for this game was to play as solid as possible and this looked to me solid enough.   The move  14...a6  would be better, covering the b5-square, thus preparing to play c5, forcing White's knight away.   This move was successfully played by Levon Aronian in a rapid game vs Alexander Grischuk.  15.e6  c5!?  the best! In the above-mentioned game, Levon went for the imprecise  15...Bxe6  and found himself in a somewhat worse position which he still managed to win. @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/1pp1bppp/p3P3/2p5/3N1B2/8/PPP2PPP/3R1RK1 w - - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16.exf7+  Kxf7  17.Nb3  a5  18.Bxc7  Bf5=∞  we have very good compensation for the sacrificed pawn, as our pair of bishops has become very active- one on f5 eyeing the c2-pawn, the 2nd one will soon go to f6- eyeing the b2-pawn. }
15. Nxe6 fxe6 16. Be3
{ With a pawn majority on the kingside, White will now try to make use of it by pushing them, then bring the king to the centre, all while trying to keep control over the d-file.   When playing this endgame it was important for me to understand what I wanted. For example, I concluded that the bishop endgame is something I'd like to avoid, especially if I'll have my pawns on the queenside fixed on the dark squares.   Imagine our pawns on c5, a5, b6, c7 and White's on c4, b3, and a4- White will eventually be able to bring their king to e4 and then push the pawn to f5, where if we don't take- allowing White to push f5-f6, our bishop will be very cramped, which could lead to a lost position because of zugzwang ideas. Taking on f5 might also prove dangerous, as White might then be able to either force a bishop trade, leading to a lost pawn endgame, or push the pawn to e6 and start collecting our pawns which will be conveniently fixed on the dark squares.   On the other hand, a rook endgame was something I would welcome, because White's rook will struggle to find squares to break in our camp, and the pawn's majority advantage on the kingside will be close to impossible to convert. Having these ideas in mind, let's see how the game continued. }
16... a5
{ A necessity, otherwise the rook would be stuck protecting the a7-pawn. } 17.
f4 g6 { Stopping White's f5 ideas for now. } 18. Kf2 Rd8 19. Rxd8+ Bxd8
{ Step 1- trading a pair of rooks is completed. } 20. Kf3 Be7 21. Rd1 h5
{ This is the ideal pawn construction on the kingside, as now White will have to trade the h-, g-, and f-pawns in order to get their e-passer. It is a convenient scenario for Black, as we'll have fewer pawns to worry about, and the smaller the portion of the board where the fight will happen- the better for the defending side. }
22. g3 b6
{ Another necessary move, as we would eventually have to protect the a5-pawn. White could either play Bd2 or Rd3-a3 in order to force us to do so. }
23. h3 Rh7
{ I was happy with the way my position looked here and decided that it was a fortress, so I could just wait around for White to show what he wanted.   The problem for White is that he can't both control the h-file and prepare the f5 breakthrough. In order to achieve the first, the rook would have to be on h1, the king on g2, and then the push on g4 would be good but would have no follow-up, as Black will simply ignore it. Taking on h5 would be met by Rxh5, where White's pawn majority would become completely ineffective, while otherwise- White can't make progress. }
24. Kg2 Rh8 25. a4 Rh7 26. b3 Rh8 27. c4 Bc5
{ Even though it's not the engine's top choice, It is the easiest path towards draw. White can't really avoid trading bishops.   27...c5  it is interesting that the computer thinks this move is better than the one I chose, even though from a human's perspective, things are exactly the opposite.   As I explained before, I wanted to avoid this pawn construction where my pawns are fixed on the dark squares because I thought that in the event of a rooks trade, the bishop endgame, as well as a pawn endgame might be lost. Our silicone friend is confident that White has no way of trading rooks, but during the game, I felt differently. }
28. Bxc5 bxc5
{ What convinced me that this is a draw was understanding that the pawn endgame after White would push g4, followed by hxg4- hxg4 would be drawn precisely because we have no pawn moves at all on the queenside, unlike the case when our pawn on c6 would be on b6 instead.   For White to try making any progress they will have to push g4. I will ignore it- the same strategy as when the bishops were still there. Taking on h5 will never be an option, as we would recapture with the rook. Bringing the king to e4 in order to prepare f5 would lose control over the h-file after hxg4. White really has nothing better to try than the above-mentioned pawn endgame which indeed happened in the game. }
29. Kf3 Ke7 30. Rd3 Rh7 31. Kg2 Rh8 32. g4
{ I could continue waiting as well, but the text move is the fastest way towards a draw- aiming for the above-mentioned pawn endgame. }
32... hxg4 33. hxg4 Rh4 34. Rg3 Kf7 35. Rd3
{ A nice try- my opponent invites me to take the g4-pawn, which would lead to a lost endgame for Black. }
35... Ke7
{ The king is back guarding the d7- and d8-squares, thus not allowing the White rook into our camp.   35...Rxg4+??  36.Kf3  Rg1  37.Rd7+  Ke8  38.Rxc7  Rb1  39.Rxc6  Rxb3+  40.Kg4+-  White is winning thanks to the very active king and rook, as opposed to Black's disastrous king on e8 and very weak pawns. }
36. Rh3 { The last try to make any progress at all. } 36... Rxh3 37. Kxh3 Kf8
{ Some sort of opposition. I needed to make sure that I'd be able to meet Kg5 with Kg7, meaning that Kh4 should be met by either Kf7 or Kh7. }
38. Kh4 Kf7 39. Kg5 Kg7 40. f5 gxf5 41. gxf5 exf5 42. Kxf5 Kf7 43. e6+ Ke7 44.
Ke5 Ke8 45. Kf6 Kf8 46. e7+ Ke8 47. Ke6
{ Imagine our c6-pawn being on b6 instead- that would be a disaster. That is exactly what I was talking about when describing which endgame I wanted to end up in and why I avoided pushing the c6-pawn to c5 and went for Bc5 instead. Thanks to this draw I ended up sharing the 2nd-7th place, securing the 2nd one due to the best tie-breaks.   Conclusions:   1. It is often useful to think of the types of endgames you could land in and assess them before making any pawn moves, as they are the only ones that can't be fixed if wrong.   2. There is nothing wrong with a passive defence if you trust your position to be a fortress. As advice: don't take too long on the clock, you should be ahead of your opponent in this department if possible, since it is them who have to 'invent the wheel' while you simply say 'pass'.   3. Don't get stressed if forgetting the theory- it has never done any good to anyone. Instead, take a breath, calm down, and simply think about what your opponent wants to do and try to apply the ideas and techniques you learned from the course. }
