[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Rapport, R. vs. Vidit, S.G. (2022)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5
8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Nc3 Be7 10. Rd1+ Ke8 11. Bg5 Bxg5 12. Nxg5 h6 13. Nge4
{ A move that doesn't score well compared to the alternative-  13.Nf3  , both examined in the course. }
13... g5
{ Vidit deviates from the line we examined in the course-  13...Ke7  , where after  14.f4  f6  Black equalizes.   Vidit's idea, or perhaps Eljanov's- the one who first played it in 2015 versus Vachier Lagrave, is to stop White from protecting the e5-pawn by means of f2-f4, even at the cost of weakening the f6-square. I believe it is a more ambitious approach compared to the one we examined which was directed to drying out the position. }
14. Ne2
{ I believe Rapport wanted to prepare the f2-f4 idea by bringing his knight to support it.   The advance  14.b4  was played in the above-mentioned game between MVL and Eljanov, as well as in another one, between Naroditsky and Hovhannisyan. If the first one ended in a draw, the 2nd one was won by Black. Both games were played with a classical time control.   White wants to play b4-b5 and then bother Black's c7-pawn in case we capture, or the c6 one if we choose to ignore the threat.  14...a6  prophylaxis against b4-b5.  15.a4  in both games, White insisted on their b4-b5 idea.   Here, Hovhannisyan deviated, playing the engine's second choice-  15...Nh4  , rerouting his knight to g6 immediately, which is also good enough for Black to keep the balance. Later he even managed to win the game.  15...Ke7  the move played by Eljanov and engine's top choice.  16.a5  MVL argues that his 3 queenside pawns are keeping Black's 4 pawns in place, meaning he can focus on creating a passer using his pawn majority on the kingside, but not before placing his knight on c5, in order to stop Black from developing their bishop, as it would have to protect the b7-pawn.   The move  16.b5?!  doesn't work now.  16...axb5  17.axb5  Rxa1  18.Rxa1  cxb5  19.Nxb5  all forced so far.  19...Bd7!  we sacrifice the c7-pawn in order to activate our rook.  20.Nxc7  Rc8  21.Nd5+  Ke6⩱  Black is better thanks to the outside passed pawn- b7. They will collect on c2 and then, e5 is also likely to fall.  16...Nh4  a typical way to reroute the knight in order to put pressure on the e5-pawn.  17.Nc5  it looks like White has achieved their first goal- locking the queenside. However, sometimes, appearances can be deceiving.  17...Ng6  eyeing the e5-pawn.  18.f3  b6=  Black comfortably equalizes and can even hope to overtake if White won't be very accurate. White's pride- the knight on c5 is pushed back, while the e5-pawn will be a constant headache.   Taking the pawn  18...Nxe5  is dangerous in view of  19.Re1  , where White will have good compensation for the sacrificed pawn. }
14... Ke7
{ The king is best placed in the centre, away from any checks on f6. } 15. Rd2
{ Prophylaxis against a potential Ne3 after the f-pawn will move forward and at the same time- White prepares to double on the d-file.   Pushing the pawn  15.f4?  is premature, as White won't be able to hold on to both their c2- and f4-pawns.  15...Ne3  a double attack on the rook and c2-pawn.  16.Rd2  Bf5  attacking the e4-knight, thus taking advantage of it not being able to go away because of the hanging c2-pawn.  17.N2g3  Bxe4  18.Nxe4  gxf4⩱  Black is better, as we're a pawn up. White might have some compensation because of our pawn being doubled, but it's not enough even for equality. We'll continue by fighting for the d-file by means of Rad8, as the trades work in the favour of the side with extra material. }
15... Be6 { Simply continuing the development. } 16. Rad1 Rad8 17. Rxd8
{ Somewhat imprecise.   The move  17.f4!  was best, as Black's knight jump on e3 no longer works so well.  17...Bd5!?  might give Black more chances.   The move  17...Ne3  is possible, but doesn't achieve much.  18.Rxd8  Rxd8  19.Rxd8  Kxd8  20.fxg5  hxg5  After this series of trades, Black threatens to capture on a2. Having a bishop vs White's knight, Black would be happy to get the a2-pawn in exchange for the g5 one, as the bishop- being a long-range piece, can fight effectively on 2 flanks in the same time- a thing which can't be said about knights.  21.b3  Nxc2  22.Nxg5=  the engines think of the position to be balanced, but I like Black's chances better in view of the higher-mentioned fact that bishops are better than knights when the fight goes on two flanks.  18.Nf6  Ne3  19.Nxd5+  Rxd5  20.Rxd5  Nxd5  notice how we've rerouted our knight from f5, where it was no longer doing much, to d5, from where it puts pressure on White's f4-pawn.  21.g3=  the position is equal, though the price of each move is higher for White, as they have to look after their f4- and e5-pawns not to get in trouble. }
17... Rxd8 18. Rxd8 Kxd8
{ Compared to the position we examined after White's @@StartFEN@@3r3r/ppp1kp2/2p1b2p/4Pnp1/4N3/8/PPPRNPPP/3R2K1 w - - 6 17@@EndFEN@@  17.f4  , White will struggle to create a passer of their own on the kingside. For now, they have to do something about the pawn which is hanging on a2. }
19. b3 Nh4
{ Vidit reroutes his knight to a better square- g6, from where the knight will both attack the e5-pawn and control the f4-square. }
20. Nc5 Bc8
{ A move that looks passive, but it's very effective, as it protects the b7-pawn while not allowing White to trade their knight for our bishop. At the same time, Black will be able to play b6, forcing White's knight away whenever he pleases. }
21. Nd4 Ng6 22. e6 fxe6 23. Ncxe6+ Ke7
{ Again, Black refuses to trade his bishop, and correctly so!  24.Nxc7  would lead to a lost position for White after  24...Bd7  @@StartBracket@@taking away the e8-square from White's knight@@EndBracket@@. The knight on c7 will be trapped. }
24. Nc5 Kd6
{ As we know, the king's position is very important in endgames, where one should try bringing it closer to the centre- exactly what Black has just done. Where is White's king? Still far from doing the same. }
25. Nd3 Ne5
{ A new trade offer, which if accepted, would bring Black's king to an even better position- on e5. }
26. Ne1 b5
{ Time has come for the pawns to advance! Black can consider even a king walk to a3 now. }
27. c3
{ White covers the b4-square while trying to secure the position of their only active piece- the knight on d4. }
27... a5
{ Aiming for b4, which would force White's c3-pawn away, leaving the knight on d4 vulnerable. }
28. f3 { Making room for the king to approach the centre. } 28... b4 29. Kf2
{ A serious mistake.   29.cxb4  was the right way to proceed, as compared to the game, Black would have to capture on b4 with the a- instead of the c-pawn.  29...axb4  30.Kf2  c5  31.Ndc2  Bf5  32.Ke2⩱  Black is still better, but White's position is defendable, as it's not easy for Black to create a passer on the queenside. }
29... c5
{ Forcing White's knight away while getting ready to recapture on b4 with the c5-pawn, which will make Black's job of creating a passed pawn on the queenside much easier, as the b4-pawn will be protected by the a5-pawn, leaving the c7-pawn a clear path to advance. }
30. Ndc2 Bf5 31. cxb4 cxb4 32. Ke3 c5 33. h3 c4 34. bxc4 Nxc4+
{ There we go, Black has managed to complete the first step of their plan of creating a passer. }
35. Kd4 Ne5
{ White is in a sort of zugzwang, as all the moves at their disposal would only worsen their position. For example  36.Ne3  loses the a2-pawn after  36...Be6  . }
36. Na1 Nc6+
{ Somewhat imprecise.   If  36...Bb1  would win a pawn, leaving White with a hopeless position.  37.a3  bxa3  38.Kc3  a2-+ }
37. Ke3 a4
{ Another imprecision, probably caused by a time trouble.  37...Bb1  was again the better move. }
38. Nd3 Kd5 39. Kd2 Kc4
{ Finally  39...Bxd3  , the time had come to trade the bishop for the knight.  40.Kxd3  Nd4-+  Black has a winning position thanks to their knight dominating the White one. As the pawn endgame is totally lost because of Black's possibility of making an outside passed pawn to distract White's king, while collecting the pawns on the kingside, White has nothing better to do than allow Black's king on c4, which would make the conversion only a matter of time. }
40. Nb2+ Kb5 41. Nc2
{ White's knight has managed to come back to the game now, making Black's job of converting his advantage quite difficult. }
41... a3 42. Nd3 Bh7
{ Black wants to attack White's a2-pawn in such a way that he won't have to worry about any forking ideas. }
43. g3 Bg8 44. Nc1 h5
{ The idea is to play h4, in order to fix White's pawn on h3, after which Black will be able to attack it by means of Be6. }
45. h4 gxh4 46. gxh4 Ne5 47. Ke3 Kc4 48. Nd4 Kc3 49. f4 Ng4+ 50. Ke4 Nf6+ 51.
Ke5 Nd7+ 52. Ke4 Nc5+ 53. Ke3 Kb2 { Poor White's pawn is now lost. } 54. Nce2
Bxa2 55. Nc6 Bc4 56. Nxb4 Bxe2 57. Kxe2 Kb3
{ White has resigned, as there's no way he could stop Black's pawn from queening.   Conclusions:   1. The move @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/ppp2pp1/2p4p/4Pn2/4N3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2R2K1 b - - 1 13@@EndFEN@@  13...g5  is an interesting attempt if one feels ambitious.   2. When the play takes place on two flanks, a bishop is usually a better piece than a knight, as it's a long rage piece, which can control both flanks.   3. In the endgame, the king's activity is an important factor, meaning that it should participate in the fight, so don't forget to bring it to the centre. }
