15... Ba6
{ A little trap! In case White doesn't protect the knight on c4 one more time, Black will be able to deliver a combination. }
16. b3
{ The rook's development,  16.Rab1??  , would walk straight into Black's trap.  16...Bxc4  17.Bxc4  Bxf2+  18.Kxf2  Qc5+-+  with a double attack and a winning position. }
16... Qe6
{ Black prepares to retreat his bishop to f8, so that the knight could jump to c5. }
17. Rad1 Bf8 18. Be3 Bb7 { Once again, the e4-pawn is in trouble. } 19. Bd3 Re8
{ Black makes a waiting move, arguing that both players have reached a position where no further improvements are possible. }
20. Ncd2 { White tries to shuffle a little bit more, by aiming for Bc4. } 20...
Ba6 21. Bxa6 Rxa6 22. Nc4 Qc6
{ It is now Black's queen turn to eye the e4-pawn. } 23. Bc1
{ Suboptimal, as it allows Black to seize the initiative.   The option with  23.Nfd2=  was the best way to protect the pawn.  23...Nc5  24.Bxc5  Qxc5=  with a balanced position, as Black has enough time to bring the rook from a6 to d8. }
23... b5 24. axb5 Qxb5
{ It is somewhat unusual that after Black has somewhat 'ruined' his pawn structure on the queenside, he has got an advantage. The point behind it is that White's pawn on b3 is now weak, while the bishop on c1 only stays in the way of his own rook to protect it via b1. }
25. Nfd2 Rb8 26. Ba3 a4 { Hoping to open up the a-file for the rook. } 27. b4
{ Another option like  27.bxa4  was possible.  27...Qxa4  28.Qxa4  Rxa4  29.Bxf8  Kxf8  would be a somewhat more pleasant endgame for Black thanks to the more harmonious piece placement. }
27... c5
{ Not allowing White to breathe- the b4-pawn is now asked a question. } 28.
bxc5 Qc6
{ Prophylaxy against Rb1. There is no need to hurry to take the c5-pawn- it will not run away. }
29. Ra1 Re8
{ Another prophylactical move- Black protects the e5-pawn with the rook so his knight would be free to move. }
30. Bb4 Nxc5 31. Ra2 Nfd7
{ Somewhat imprecise, Black could aim for a more active placement of the knight, so  31...Nh5  would be better.  32.Ne3  Nf4⩱  Black is better thanks to the weakness of the d3-square, the outside passed a-pawn, and the more active pieces. }
32. Rd1 Rea8 33. Ra3 Ne6 34. Rb1 Bc5
{ Better was  34...Nf4  immediately, with the idea of bringing the second knight to c5 and then to d3. }
35. Qd1
{ The trade  35.Bxc5  was better, taking advantage of that Black would lose a pawn if recapturing with the d7-knight.  35...Nexc5  36.Ne3  the worst is now behind for White, as their rook can come to b4, from where it will keep an eye both on the e4- and a4-pawns, while their knight could land on d5. }
35... Nf4 36. Qf1 Kh7 37. g3 Ne6 38. h4
{ White tries to limit Black's knights, by taking away the f4- and g5-squares from them. }
38... Bxb4 39. cxb4
{ Giving away the control over the d4-square, but getting a passer on the b-file. }
39... Nd4 40. Na5
{ Not a good square for the knight. As a rule, knights feel much better in the centre of the board, as from there they have the biggest number of possible jumps compared to when they're on the edge of the board.  40.Ne3  would be better. }
40... Qb5 41. Qd1
{ An unfortunate way of avoiding the queen's trade.   Playing with the king  41.Kg2  would be more tenacious, even though still unpleasant.  41...Rd6  42.Nf3  Nb6⩱  Black still holds an advantage, thanks to the more active pieces and the blockade on the b5-square, but White's hopes of defending it are still very much alive. }
41... Rf6
{ Somewhat imprecise.   The option with  41...Rc8!  was the most precise move.  42.Kg2  Rc2-+  would leave White completely paralyzed. }
42. Kg2 Rc8
{ Black still has a decisive advantage, but to prove it- he has to find a very strong continuation on the next move. }
43. Rb2 { Covering the c2-square. } 43... Nc5
{ Gives away a big part of the advantage.   A beautiful way of finishing the game would be  43...Rc2!!  44.Rxc2  Nxc2  45.Rc3   After  45.Qxc2  , accepting the sacrifice, losses on the spot.  45...Qe2  White has no way of protecting the f2-pawn without losing material.  46.Rf3  Rxf3-+  45...Nd4-+  White has just too many weaknesses- the f2-pawn, the b4-pawn. He can't defend them all. }
44. Qf1 Qxf1+ 45. Kxf1
{ After the trade  45.Nxf1  Nb5   45...Nxe4?  46.Rxa4  with big chances for White to save the game.  46.Ra1  Nd3  47.Rd2∓  Black would still have a lot of work ahead to win this game. }
45... Ncb3
{ Throws away all the advantage.   45...Nb5!  46.Re3  a3  47.Ra2  Na4-+  White's position is collapsing because of Black's a-passer and the very strong knights. }
46. Naxb3 axb3 47. Nxb3 Rc3
{ Perhaps Black hoped that he could use this pin win the game. } 48. b5 Rb6
{ The move  48...Rff3??  would even lose now.  49.b6  Rxb3  50.Raxb3  Rxb3  51.Rxb3  Nxb3  52.b7+-  the pawn can't be stopped. }
49. Nxd4
{ After the line  49.Kg2!  Rxb5   49...Nxb5  50.Raa2  protects the rook, so that the knight can jump.  50...Nd6  51.Nd2=  50.Nxd4  too many rooks are hanging now, but you can't take them all.  50...Rxb2  51.Rxc3  exd4=  with a drawn rook endgame. }
49... Rxa3 50. Nc6 f6
{ This endgame is interesting, but it is not our point of study, so we'll finish the analysis here. Adams had some chances to save the game, but in the end, his opponent proved more tenacious. }
51. h5 Rc3 52. Ne7 Rc5 53. Rd2 Rcxb5 54. Nf5 Rb8 55. Kg2 R5b7 56. Kh3 Rb2 57.
