[Black "Nepomniachtchi, I. vs. Firouzja, A. (2024)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. c3 O-O 6. O-O d5 7. exd5 Qxd5 8.
Bc4 Qd8
{ As indicated in the course, White has some other moves to choose from in this position-  9.Nbd2  and  9.Bg5  . }
9. b4 Be7 10. Nbd2 a6 { Prophylaxis against both, b5 and Bb5  . } 11. a4
{ Stopping Black from playing b7-b5. } 11... Bf5 12. Qc2 Nd5
{ Improving the position of the knight, which wasn't doing much on f6. It may now head towards b6, from where it would attack the bishop on c4, which is White's most active piece.   12...Qd7  is also possible.  13.Bb2   13.Ba3  preparing b5.  13...Bd6  protecting the e5-pawn, so that in case of  14.b5  the knight could go away on a5.  14.Rfe1  b5!  Black doesn't have any problem whatsoever, as after  15.axb5  axb5  16.Bxb5  , there's the tactical shot  16...Nxb4!  . 1/2 @@StartBracket@@75@@EndBracket@@-1/2 @@StartBracket@@75@@EndBracket@@ Duda,J @@StartBracket@@2738@@EndBracket@@-Anand,V @@StartBracket@@2753@@EndBracket@@ Zagreb CRO 2021  13...Bd6  14.Ne4  Nxe4  15.dxe4  Be6  16.Bd5!?  an interesting attempt for White to build some initiative.  16...f6  freeing the f7-square for the queen.  17.a5  Qf7=  White may hope for some visual advantage, though in reality- Black is completely fine, as we'll continue by bringing our rooks to the centre by means of Rf@@StartBracket@@a@@EndBracket@@d8. }
13. Ne4
{ White needs to close the path of our bishop towards their d3-pawn, otherwise, our knight's jump to b6 would cause them a lot of headaches, or should I say 'pawnaches'? }
13... Bg4 14. Qa2
{ White defends indirectly, by attacking our knight on d5, not giving us time to take on f3.   The option  14.Ne1  is somewhat passive.  14...Qd7  15.Ng3  Nf4↑  Black starts to develop an initiative, that's why White chose to sacrifice a pawn instead, thus keeping to be the one who puts pressure. }
14... Nb6 15. Bb3 Bxf3 16. gxf3 Qxd3
{ The most principled, accepting the offered pawn.   Playing  16...Qd7  would be more cautious, but White would be able to get an edge.  17.a5  Nc8  18.Qe2  White is slightly better, as they got the pair of bishops without sacrificing a pawn. }
17. Kg2
{ An interesting idea by Nepomniachtchi- he sacrificed the d3-pawn in order to get piece activity and the pair of bishops, not caring too much about the shattered pawn structure on the kingside. }
17... Qd7
{ The move  17...Qd8  would transpose to the text after  18.Rd1  Qe8  . } 18.
Rd1 Qe8
{ The best square for the queen, as it's in close proximity to the king, which might use the extra protection. }
19. h4
{ In the spirit of Alpha Zero! White pushes their marginal pawn, aiming to go all the way to h6 in the hope of provoking some weaknesses in Black's camp. }
19... Nc8
{ Firouzja correctly reroutes his knight, as it was no longer of use on b6. }
20. h5 Kh8
{ It is by no means a bad move, but it allows White some extra ideas.   The advance  20...h6!?  would be better according to the engine. Humanwise, it is hard to commit to such a move, as one could worry about both a potential sacrifice on h6 and some trouble over the b1-h7 diagonal.  21.Ng3  Kh8  preparing f7-f5.  22.Qe2  f5⩱  Black is better thanks to the superior pawn structure and White's initiative fading away. }
21. h6 g5
{ Black takes advantage of the position of White's king, which doesn't allow them to capture on g5 in view of  22.--  Rg8  . }
22. Qd2 { White hopes to offer a queen trade by means of  22...--  23.Qd7  . }
22... Nd6 { Covering the d-file while improving the knight's position. } 23.
Bb2 { Nepomniachtchi prepares an x-ray over the long dark diagonal. } 23... Nf5
{ 23...f6  Would have perhaps been somewhat better, as it wouldn't allow White's queen infiltrating in Black's camp.  24.b5!?  An interesting sacrifice which perhaps Firouzja didn't like.  24...axb5  25.axb5  Rxa1  26.Rxa1  Nxb5  27.Qd5  Nd6∞  White has enough compensation for the game to be balanced thanks to their piece activity. }
24. Qd7 Nh4+ 25. Kf1 f5
{ Taking the f6-square under control, while closing the b1-h7 diagonal.   The knight  25...Nxf3  would be asking for trouble.  26.Nf6!  Qc8!   26...Bxf6??  would be a blunder.  27.Qf5!  a triple attack! The bishop on f6 and the knight on f3 are hanging, while the most important threat is coming from the b1-h7 diagonal- White wants to play 28.Bc2 and deliver then mate on h7.  27...Nh2+  28.Kg2  Qe7  29.Bc2+-  Black has no good way of defending against the mate on h7.  27.Qxc8  Rfxc8  28.Nd5=∞  Black is two pawns up, but White has very serious compensation for them thanks to their piece activity and weaknesses in Black's camp, as well as Black's exposed king. }
26. Ng3 Nxf3 27. b5
{ White is two pawns down, so he can't lose time, needing to build on on his initiative, making threats with each of his moves. }
27... f4 { Black answers with a threat of his own! } 28. Ne4 Na5
{ Allows White the possibility to improve the bishop's position.   28...Qh5!  threatening to play  29.--  Nh2+  , which would lead to a perpetual, as White doesn't have a good way to stop it. @@StartFEN@@r4r1k/1ppQb2p/p1n4P/1P2p1pq/P3Np2/1BP2n2/1B3P2/R2R1K2 w - - 2 29@@EndFEN@@  29.bxc6  Nh2+  30.Ke1  Nf3+  31.Kf1   31.Ke2??  losses.  31...Nd4+  32.Kd2  Qe2+  33.Kc1  Nxb3+-+  Black gets back the sacrificed material and will play 34...Rad8 on the next move, leaving White completely lost.  31...Nh2+  32.Kg1  Nf3+=  with a perpetual. }
29. Be6 { Now the h3-c8 diagonal is safely guarded. } 29... Qg6
{ 29...g4!  was necessary.  30.Qxc7   30.Bxg4?  Nh2+  31.Ke1  Nxg4  32.Qxg4  Qf7∓  Black has sacrificed back a pawn, but has solved all his problems by getting rid of White's light-squared bishop.  30...g3!  going for counterplay by creating threats against White's king. The position would stay very complicated, with chances for both sides. }
30. Qxe7 Qxh6 31. Bf7
{ 31.Bd5!  would be even better.  31...Qh3+  32.Ke2  Qg4  33.Nf6+-  with a winning advantage for White. }
31... Qh3+ 32. Ke2 Qf5 33. Bd5
{ Good enough- White protects everything and enjoys a decisive advantage thanks to their extra piece and Black's exposed king. }
33... Rae8 34. Qxc7 Qg4 35. Kd3
{ Some accuracy was still needed. The text move is the only winning one.   35.Qxa5??  being greedy would cost White half point.  35...Nd4+  36.Kf1  Qe2+  37.Kg1  Qg4+  38.Kf1=  with a perpetual. }
35... Rd8 36. c4 Rxd5+ 37. cxd5 Qh3
{ Black hopes to be able to jump with their knight, delivering an unpleasant check, as White can't go with his king on c2 in view of Rc8. }
38. Ng3
{ Perhaps not the most precise, but the safest.   38.Nd6!  Black doesn't have any good knight jumps.  38...Nd4+  39.Ke4+-  it is a bit hard to believe that White's king is safe in the middle of the board, but it was actually the case. Black's position is hopeless. }
38... Nc4
{ The line  38...fxg3  39.Bxe5+  Nxe5+  40.Qxe5+  Kg8  41.Qxg5++-  doesn't work. }
39. Qxc4 fxg3 40. fxg3 axb5 41. axb5 Rc8 42. Rh1 Qd7 43. Qe4 Kg8 44. Ke3 Nd4
45. Bxd4
{ Black resigned, as he's simply a rook down. An exciting game, full of mistakes from both sides.  Conclusions:  1. On move 20, it was better to stop White's pawn from advancing to h6 by playing @@StartFEN@@r1n1qrk1/1pp1bppp/p1n5/4p2P/PP2N3/1BP2P2/Q4PK1/R1BR4 b - - 0 20@@EndFEN@@  22...h6  , which would make White's attack less dangerous.  2. In a dynamic position- time is vital. Don't allow your opponent time to breathe and use it to create threats with each of your moves instead. }
