[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Wang, H. vs. Howell, D. (2023)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. Re1
{ The second most popular move after  5.d4  . White aims for a symmetrical position where he will try to use his advantage in development. }
5... Nd6 6. Nxe5
{ The mainline. The bishop on b5 is untouchable in view of  6...Nxb5  7.Nxc6+  , where Black loses the queen. }
6... Be7
{ Covering the e-file and planning to castle short after White deals with the imminent threat of  7.--  Nxb5  . }
7. Bf1 Nxe5 8. Rxe5 O-O
{ Black's king is safe and Howell will now focus on completing the development of his queenside. }
9. d4 Bf6 10. Re1 Nf5
{ It was Black's plan all along- vacate the d-file for the pawn to move forward, opening up the light-squared bishop. }
11. c3 d5 { The light-squared bishop has become alive! } 12. Bf4
{ White simply continues the development. } 12... c6 13. Nd2
{ With White's knight aiming for the f3-square, Black has two fine options here. Both of them were discussed in the course. }
13... Nh4
{ Is interesting, not allowing White's knight on f3 so easily.   And  13...Bg5  was the other possibility. The idea is to trade the dark-squared bishops first.  14.Bxg5  Qxg5  15.Nf3  Qf6  16.Ne5  Nd6=  White's knight is slightly more active than ours, this being the only reason why the engine gives a 0.09 advantage to White. }
14. h3
{ Covers the g4-square, so that one won't have to worry about a potential pin when White plays Nf3. }
14... Bd7 { Black finishes the development. } 15. Bd3 Re8
{ Offering a rooks trade, as Black would like to liquidate as many pieces of the board as possible. }
16. Qc2
{ Wang Hao plays a logical, multifunctional move. On one hand, he prepares to recapture on e1 with the rook, while on the other hand, he attacks Black's pawn on h7. }
16... g6
{ The best. Black solves the problem of the hanging pawn while taking control of the f5-square which can be used for Black's light pieces. }
17. Rxe8+ Qxe8 18. g3 Nf5 19. Nf3 Ng7
{ Another plus of the h7-, g6-, f7-pawn construction becomes evident here- Black uses the g7-square for his knight to retreat, preparing to offer another piece trade by means of Bf5. Don't forget that the pawn on h3 is also hanging at the moment. }
20. Re1
{ With  20.g4  , White could have tried to prevent Black's Bf5 idea.  20...Ne6  21.Bg3  c5  Black can start challenging White in the centre.  22.dxc5  Nxc5  the knight now heads to e4.  23.Re1  Qd8  24.Bf1  Ne4=  with a balanced position thanks to the slight weakening of White's kingside and Black's fantastic knight on e4. A possible way to continue is bringing the queen to the queenside by means of Qa5, while the rook can find place on e8. }
20... Qc8
{ The best square for the queen- the B+Q battery prevents White's g4 ideas. }
21. h4
{ 21.g4??  no longer works.  21...Bxg4  22.hxg4  Qxg4+-+  With a double attack and a winning position for Black. }
21... Bf5 { As promised, Black offers another piece trade. } 22. Bg5
{ An interesting try- White offers a piece trade of his own, hoping to achieve a change of the pawn structure on the kingside. }
22... Bxg5
{ 22...Bxd3  was also possible.  23.Qxd3  Qd8=  Black could have avoided the change of the pawn structure this way. The position is only slightly more pleasant for White. Black will continue by pushing h5 and then bringing the knight to f5. }
23. hxg5
{ One should always evaluate carefully such changes in the pawn structure, as Black will now have to answer some questions regarding the newly weakened f6- and h6-squares, as well as the semi-opened h-file. }
23... Bxd3 24. Qxd3 Qf5
{ This is the solution Howell had in mind, White won't have the opportunity to use those weakened squares. }
25. Qxf5
{ 25.Qe3  Trying to keep the queens on the board doesn't prove of much effect.  25...Re8  26.Ne5  Ne6=  Black has enough counterplay as he'll apply pressure on the g5-pawn. }
25... Nxf5 26. g4 Nd6 27. Re7
{ White's rook is very nice and active, but it won't be able to keep its position }
27... Rd8
{ First of all, Black needed to take the d7-square under control in order to avoid getting in trouble after Rd7- where the knight on d6 would have to move away, leaving the b7-pawn at White's mercy. }
28. Ne5
{ Another nice and active move. White's idea is to play  28...--  29.Rc7  followed by a knight rerouting- Nd7-f6. }
28... Kf8 29. Rc7 Ke8
{ Black's king is in time to cover the d7-square so that White's knight no longer has a route to his knight's avail. }
30. f3 Rc8 { The last piece trade offer- White's rook can't really escape it. }
31. Rd7
{ White offered a draw, as after  31...Rd8  , he would have to either trade rooks or repeat the position.   Conclusions:   1. The whole concept of this line for Black is to offer piece trades, one after another, but not before carefully considering which are White's threats.   2. The best pawn construction for Black on the kingside is h7, g6, f7, as it not only solves any problems regarding a potentially hanging pawn on h7, but also vacates the g7-square for the knight, from where it can support the Bf5 piece trade idea, or the knight can jump to f5 itself.   The line after @@StartFEN@@2r1k3/ppR2p1p/2pn2p1/3pN1P1/3P2P1/2P2P2/PP6/6K1 w - - 1 31@@EndFEN@@  31.Rxc8+  Nxc8  32.Kf2  Nd6  33.Ke3  Ke7=  would be an equal knight endgame. Black will continue by pushing f6, whereas White will have no real chances of improving his position. }
