[Black "Hou, Y. vs. Kramnik, V. (2015)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. Qe2
{ The best scoring move. The idea is to protect the e4-pawn without committing the pawn to d2-d3, thus keeping the possibility of playing c2-c3, and d2-d4 in one go. }
4... Bc5
{ The best square for the bishop as it fights against potential d4 ideas. } 5.
c3
{ The most played and best scoring move for White as she's getting ready to play d4.   The trade  5.Bxc6!?  forces Black to react in an unusual way.  The best way to recapture is  5...bxc6!  , as the light-squared bishop will need to use the a6-f1 diagonal.  6.Nxe5  Qe7  Black will be able to overtake thanks to the pair of bishops, see the corresponding chapter in the course for more. }
5... O-O 6. d3 h6
{ Stopping White's bishop from developing to  g5  . A pawn aggression by means of  7.g4  is premature- Black will simply take it-  7...Nxg4  - attacking the f2-pawn. }
7. Nbd2
{ A move which we haven't examined in the course, unlike the most popular  7.O-O  Re8  , where Black won't face too many problems either.   Once again  7.Bxc6  doesn't work well  7...bxc6  8.Nxe5  Re8  9.d4  Bb6⩱  Black is better thanks to the advantage in development. }
7... d6 { Black protects the e5-pawn and continues the development. } 8. O-O
{ After  8.h3!?  , preparing g4 without castling short doesn't work well for White.  8...Ne7  rerouting the knight to f4.  9.g4  Ng6  10.Nf1  d5  when one attacks on one of the flanks, the other should come up with a break in the centre, as Black has just done!  11.g5  Nh5  pinpointing the weakness of the f4-square.  12.gxh6  Ngf4  13.Bxf4  Nxf4  14.Qd2  c6  15.hxg7  Re8  White's pawn on g7 will actually cover Black's king very nicely.  16.Ba4  dxe4∓  it is interesting that White's king will now be in trouble, with incoming checks on either g2 or d3. }
8... Ne7 { The typical knight rerouting to g6. } 9. d4 a6
{ A nice intermediate move! } 10. dxc5
{ The move  10.Ba4  was the alternative.  10...exd4  11.cxd4  Ba7∞  with a balanced position. }
10... axb5 11. cxd6 Qxd6
{ The trade  11...cxd6!?  would also be interesting.  12.Qxb5  Qc7  Black has sacrificed a pawn and White now struggles to finish the development, as their knight on d2 is blocking the bishop and it can't leave because of the pawn on e4.  13.c4  going for another diagonal for the bishop.  13...Be6  14.b3  Nc6=∞  it is now White's queen which is in trouble, as after 15...Ra5, it will have no squares to retreat to. Black has more than sufficient compensation. }
12. Qxb5 Ng6
{ Black wants to use the advantage in the development and the fact that White's knight has to stay on d2 for now, protecting the e4-pawn. }
13. Re1
{ Playing  13.Nc4  was the best.  13...Qd3  Black's queen pins White's c4-knight while attacking the e4-pawn in the same time.  14.Re1  Be6  15.Na3  Qd6=∞  Black has very good compensation for the sacrificed pawn, but with precise play, White should be able to avoid trouble. }
13... b6 { Opening additional possibilities for the light-squared bishop. } 14.
Nc4
{ Looks active, but it actually only leads to trouble for White.   Would be perhaps better:  14.Qb4  c5  15.Qb3  Ba6  16.a4  Bd3⩱  Black is better and even though it's nothing critical yet, White has an unpleasant job ahead. }
14... Qe6
{ White can't capture on e5 now, as she'd lose a piece after  15.Nfxe5  Ba6  , or  15.Ncxe5  Ba6  . }
15. Ne3
{ 15.Ncd2  is a sad move to play, but it was perhaps necessary.  15...Rxa2  16.Rxa2  Qxa2  17.Qc4  Qa7⩱  Black would be better here as well, but it's not so much. }
15... Nxe4 { Why not take a juicy, central pawn indeed? } 16. Qd5 Nc5
{ After  16...Qxd5?  , it would give away the whole advantage.  17.Nxd5  Nc5  18.Nxc7⩲  It is Black now who's in some of a trouble. }
17. b4 Bb7 { Another nice intermediate move! } 18. Qxe6 Nxe6 19. Nf5 Rfd8
{ The rook now aims for the c3-pawn. } 20. a4 Rd3
{ Black now has a decisive advantage, as he'll win a pawn in addition to his very active and well-coordinated pieces. }
21. Be3 Rxc3 22. a5 Rb3 23. axb6 cxb6 24. Rxa8+ Bxa8 25. Bxb6
{ Losses on the spot, but the position was anyway very bad for White. } 25...
Bxf3 26. gxf3 Ng5 27. Kh1 Nxf3 28. Re4 Nf4
{ White resigned, as there's no way to avoid further material losses in view of a mate being threatened on the back rank.  Conclusions:   1. One should always consider sacrificing a pawn in order to get the initiative, especially when the opponent struggles to finish their development.   2. Don't make automatic moves! One should always be alert for intermediate moves, which can change the course of the game.   3. Once seizing the momentum, keep creating threats, not allowing your opponent to breathe! }
