1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. Re1 Nd6 6. a4
{ An interesting move played by many top grandmasters. The idea behind it is simple- protect the bishop and get ready to recapture on b5 with the pawn. }
6... Be7
{ Black continues the development, planning to castle short. Taking on b5 would be a bad idea, as after  6...Nxb5  7.axb5  , the knight on c6 would have to answer unpleasant questions. }
7. Nc3 { White delays taking the e5-pawn back, trying to develop first. } 7...
a6
{ Asking the bishop a question. We know that obtaining the pair of bishops is convenient for Black, meaning White has to retreat. }
8. Bf1 f6
{ As White delayed for so long getting his central pawn back, why not protect it indeed? }
9. d4 { White hopes to either open the e-file or get back his pawn. } 9... Nf7
{ The knight comes to defend e5 one more time. } 10. Bc4
{ White attacks the f7-knight, hoping that after capturing it, he'd be able to win the e5-pawn.   The move  10.Nd5  is the move checked in the course and the engine's top choice.  10...d6  stabilizing the e5-pawn while opening the light-squared bishop.  11.Bc4  O-O  would transpose to the game. }
10... d6 { Black simply protects the e5-pawn. } 11. Nd5
{ The trade  11.Bxf7+  might look dangerous for Black, but it's nothing to be scared of.  11...Kxf7  with White's light-squared bishop gone, Black's king feels safe on f7.   After  12.Qd3  White hopes to stop Black's rook from sliding to e8, after which the king can make an artificial castle by moving to g8.  However, with  12...Nb4∓  Black is a healthy pawn up as White can't keep the position of their queen on the b1-h7 diagonal. Both  13.Qc4  and  13.Qe4  would be met by  13...d5  , otherwise Black will bring their rook to e8, and then the king will go to g8. }
11... O-O 12. c3
{ White consolidates his centre.   Playing with the rook  12.Ra3!?  is the move studied in the course- a typical rook lift, hoping to bring the rook to business as fast as possible.  12...Kh8  prophylaxis- the x-ray over the a2-g8 diagonal was unpleasant. White is yet to prove their desired compensation for the sacrificed pawn, while Black can simply continue the development by means of Bg4, then Qd7. }
12... Kh8
{ The same idea as after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1pp1bnpp/p1np1p2/3Np3/P1BP4/5N2/1PP2PPP/R1BQR1K1 w - - 2 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Ra3  - to move away from White's bishop x-ray over the a2-g8 diagonal. }
13. Ba2
{ White hints that he might want to build a battery on the b1-h7 diagonal. }
13... Qd7
{ The best. Black's idea is to play Bd8, then Ne7, in order to trade White's most active piece- the knight on d5. }
14. Nh4
{ Opening-up the diagonal for the queen to jump over on the kingside, after which threats like Ng6 would be on the table. }
14... g5 { Not so fast, the knight is forced away. } 15. Nf3 Bd8
{ Black's securing the position of his dark-squared bishop, but this time, the idea is different, as he can no longer offer the knight trade on e7 because of the hanging pawn on f6. However,  16...g4  is now an unpleasant threat, as after  17.Nh4  , Black can continue harassing White's knight by means of  17...f5  . }
16. Be3
{ 16.b4  was a better try, the idea is to push Black's knight away by means of b5.  16...g4  17.Nd2  Ng5  18.Nf1∞  the position remains very complicated, but White has yet to prove his compensation for the sacrificed pawn. With the f6-pawn protected by the rook on f8, the Ne7 idea is back on the table. }
16... e4
{ Once again- the best. Black takes advantage of the fact that White is no longer controlling the e4-square. }
17. Nd2 f5
{ A move of two purposes- protect the e4-pawn and threaten to trap White's bishop by means of f4. }
18. g3
{ The advance  18.f4  was the best way of avoiding for the bishop to be trapped.  18...g4  19.Bf2  h5  20.h4  White could hope to keep the balance here, as the extra pawn advantage is not easy to convert in a position with such a closed pawn structure. }
18... Nb8
{ This move is a bit slow, though not without any merit. Black intends to play  19.--  c6  , pushing White's knight away.   It would have been better to bring the other knight to the party with @@StartFEN@@r1bb1r1k/1ppq1n1p/p1np4/3N1pp1/P2Pp3/2P1B1P1/BP1N1P1P/R2QR1K1 b - - 0 18@@EndFEN@@  18...Nh6!  , with threats like Ng4, or Qg7, and f4 in the air.  19.f4  Ng4∓  Black has quite a significant advantage, as in addition to the extra pawn, White's king has some questions to answer. Black can continue with the idea of offering a knight trade by means of Ne7. }
19. c4
{ Looking for counterplay by challenging Black's centre with  19.f3  was better  19...c6  20.Nb4  a5  21.Nc2  d5⩱  Black is better, but some serious work is still ahead. }
19... c6 20. Nc3 Nh6
{ Back to the right track. Black's advantage is decisive. } 21. Nf1 Qg7
{ X-raying White's king and threatening to play f4. } 22. Bd2 Bf6
{ After  22...Qxd4??  , White could turn the tables with  23.Nxe4!  fxe4  24.Bc3+-  White wins, as Black's queen is trapped. }
23. Qc1 Bxd4 24. Bxg5 Ng4 { The f2-pawn is in serious trouble now. } 25. Re2
Nd7 { Bringing one more piece into the attack. } 26. h3 Nde5
{ Black ignores White's threat of taking the knight on g4 and creates one of his own- a fork on f3 is imminent. }
27. Kg2 Nd3 28. Qd2 f4 { Poor White's king... } 29. Rxe4
{ Doesn't help because of  29.hxg4  f3+  30.Kh1  fxe2-+ } 29... Ngxf2 30. gxf4
Bxh3+ 31. Kh2 Bxc3
{ White resigned in the face of multiple threats.   Conclusions:   1. When struggling to find a way to improve your own pieces, think of which of your opponent's pieces are best and if you can- trade them @@StartBracket@@see the Ne7 idea to trade the knight from d5@@EndBracket@@.   2. When attacking, don't forget to bring all of your forces to the party- the more the better. }
