1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ This is the first game where I played the Berlin with the black pieces. It happened during the first round of the 2024 European Women's Championship.   It might look as a rather strange idea to employ this system when playing versus a lower rated opponent, but my strategy for this championship was to play sound, solid chess and to have the mindset that a draw with Black was a good result, while I would try to push with White. }
4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6 6. dxe5
{ At this point, I remember thinking why I chose to play the Berlin, that the game will be over in a few moves, ending with the famous move repetition. I had to calm down and remind myself that according to my strategy for the tournament, a quick draw with the Black pieces would be a welcome outcome since I'd be saving important energy for the later games. }
6... Nxb5 7. a4 Nbd4 8. Nxd4 d5
{ At this point, I was already mentally prepared to sign the scoresheets and return to my room. }
9. Nc3
{ Surprise! My opponent, a younger player from Azerbaidjan showed ambition, avoiding the famous drawing line. She came up with this move at the board, as she took quite some time before making it.   The trade  9.exd6  would lead to the drawing line.  9...Nxd4  10.Qxd4  Qxd6  11.Qe4+  Qe6  12.Qd4  Qd6=  with a repetition. }
9... Be7 { As recommended in the course, I simply continued the development. }
10. Nf3
{ White chooses a different way to protect the e5-pawn, while attacking Black's d5-pawn in the same time.   The advance  10.f4  is the move analysed in the course, protecting the e5-pawn.  10...Nxd4  11.Qxd4  c6  Black protects the d5-pawn while preparing to offer a queens trade by means of  12.--  Qb6  , the position is balanced. }
10... Be6 11. Re1
{ An interesting alternative was  11...Qd7  , keeping the option of castling long as well. }
11... O-O 12. Ne2
{ The knight on c3 wasn't doing much, so White reroutes it to either f4 or g3. }
12... Qd7
{ The development is fully completed now with the rooks being connected. } 13.
Bg5
{ Covering the g4-square,  13.h3  was more precise.  13...h6  Black does the same, covering the g5-square.  14.c3∞  the position is balanced. Black can choose from playing f6, or first bringing the a-rook to the centre and then looking for ways to open up the pair of bishops. }
13... Bg4
{ This pin looked more interesting to me, as I invited White to take on e7, when I could capture back with the knight, which I thought would do better on the kingside.   My 1st candidate move was  13...Bxg5  , which also looked quite good.  14.Nxg5  h6  this would keep the game alive.   14...Nxe5?!  dries out the position too much.  15.Nf4  Bg4  16.Qxd5=  with an equal position.  15.Nxe6  fxe6  Black is slightly better thanks to the semi-opened f-file and the pressure one can apply against the e5-pawn. }
14. Bxe7 Nxe7 15. Qd3
{ The move  15.Nf4  was the best one.  15...Ng6  16.Nxg6   16.Nxd5?!  might be a bit dangerous.  16...Rfd8  17.Ne3  Qxd1  18.Rexd1  Bxf3  19.gxf3  Nxe5⩱  Black is slightly better thanks to the superior pawn structure.  16...hxg6  17.h3  Bxf3  18.Qxf3=  the position is very drawish, with all the light pieces off the board. }
15... Bxf3
{ Too hasty, there was no rush to make the trade, it was better to finish my knight rerouting first.   15...Ng6  now the capture on f3 is a serious threat, as the e5-pawn will be left unprotected.  16.Ned4  c5  17.Nb5  Be6⩱  Black is better thanks to the nice centre and the bishop which is superior to the knight. }
16. Qxf3 Ng6
{ I think that I was still in the 'making a draw' mode, this being the reason I didn't realize I could start pushing for more. }
17. Nf4 Nxf4 18. Qxf4
{ With all the light pieces off the board, the position has dried out significantly, but it still bears some interesting resources for both sides. }
18... c5 { It makes sense to take some space in the centre. } 19. Re3
{ My opponent signals that she'd like to slide the rook to the kingside and try creating some threats against my king. }
19... Rae8
{ Preparing a rook lift of my own to e6, from where it can both go on the kingside if needed, or I could stack up my pieces on the e-file, in order to put pressure on the e5-pawn. }
20. Rd1 d4 { With the d-pawn safe, I threaten to capture the a4-pawn. } 21. Rg3
Re6
{ As planned, the rook comes to aid the king.   If  21...Qxa4??  , it would be a terrible blunder.  22.Qh6  g6  23.Rh3+-  there is no way to stop the mate in one threat. }
22. Qg4 f5 23. exf6 Rfxf6
{ Here I started to become optimistic about my chances, as my pieces have gained some activity. I liked my controlling the e-file the most, while the semi-opened f-file was a nice additional bonus, together with White's weak a4-pawn. }
24. b3 Qe7 { Mate in two is a serious threat. } 25. Kf1
{ White's king is now in a precarious position for an indefinite time.   Would have been better  25.h3  Re2  ,  perhaps this is the move my opponent didn't like, with a double attack on the c2- and f2-pawns.  26.c3  Rexf2   26...dxc3??  27.Rd7+-  White suddenly wins.  27.cxd4∞  the position is balanced. }
25... Re4 26. Qg5 Re5
{ The most precise way to continue is  26...h6  .  Compared to the move played in the game, it has the advantage of creating a 'luft' for the king on h7, so that in many lines it will be able to hide there, not worrying about back rank issues.  27.Qd2  Rfe6⩱  the move  28.--  Re2  is an unpleasant threat. }
27. Qd2 Rfe6 28. Rf3
{ The advance  28.c3!  is a nice counterattacking resource!  28...Re2  29.Qc1  my pieces look very good, but I can't do much with them- White has enough counterplay to keep the balance. }
28... Re2 29. Qc1 Qh4
{ Being in possession of the initiative, I try to build on it, making threats with each move. }
30. Qf4
{ Being in time trouble, my opponent faultily decided that the rook endgame might bear some drawing chances.   After  30.Kg1?  Qe4-+  Black wins in view of the double threat of either taking on c2 or delivering mate on the back rank.   However,  30.c3!  would be the best defense.  30...Qxh2  31.Rh3  Qe5  32.cxd4  cxd4  33.Qc8+  Re8∓  Black is a pawn up, but the job is far from being done, White can put up resistance. }
30... Qxf4 31. Rxf4 Rxc2 32. Re1 Rxe1+ 33. Kxe1 Rc3 34. b4 b6
{ The easiest, as two connected passed pawns assure an easy win in most of the rook endgames. }
35. bxc5 bxc5 36. Rf5 c4 37. Rc5
{ The line  37.Ra5  Kf7  38.Rxa7+  Ke6  39.Rxg7  d3-+  would be not so different from what happened in the game. }
37... d3 38. a5 Kf7 39. Rc7+ Kf6 40. Kd2 Rc2+ 41. Kd1 Ke5 42. Rxa7 Kd4
{ White resigned, as the Black king will come to c3, after which the threats of mate combined with those of promoting will be unstoppable.   Conclusions:   1. When your opponent surprises you with a suboptimal move, be prepared to switch your mindset from the 'making a draw' mode to a 'pressing' mode.   2. Every position, however dry it might look at first sight should be taken seriously. The game isn't over until the scoresheets are signed.   3. Playing for a draw without offering it is a strategy that can sometimes bring unexpectedly good results, especially when playing versus lower-rated opponents. Combine it with creating small threats, asking little questions like- would you like to trade this piece or not, would you like to push that pawn or not, and you might get some time advantage which can become the deciding factor closer to the end of the game, even if the position is objectively still equal. }
